[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Welcome to the course!   The main objective of this course is to provide you with a practical and ambitious repertoire against the rock-solid Petroff defense.   This defense is very reliable and has been played at the highest echelons of chess by a whole host of top players such as Anand, Kramnik, and Caruana to name a few. The latter used it to great effect in the 2018 Candidates tournament, scoring several important wins with Black.   After countless hours of analysis examining all of White’s major options, I came to the conclusion that the mainline with 3. Nxe5 4. Nf3 5. d4 is White’s best chance for an advantage. While I cannot guarantee an advantage in every single variation, we’ll be putting maximum pressure on Black’s position and making it as hard as possible for him to equalize. There are only a couple of lines where Black can equalize and, even in these few instances, you can still count on a position that is easier to play or one where you can press for many moves with minimal risk.   I strongly believe that searching for the best moves for both sides and remaining as objective as possible is key when preparing an effective repertoire. My hope is that this repertoire is also useful for Petroff players with the black pieces.  Inside this course, you’ll find cutting-edge analysis powered by the latest versions of the revolutionary neural network engines Stockfish and Leela running on superfast cloud servers. I found many improvements over current theory and dozens of novelties ensuring you’re ready to take on even the most booked-up opponents! Therepertoire clashes file shows you how to get an advantage against the recommendations in all the recent Petroff repertoire books.   Apart from the Petroff, I’ve also covered all of Black’s major alternatives to 2...Nc6 and 2...Nf6. I map out a route towards a clear advantage @@StartBracket@@or an outright winning position!@@EndBracket@@ against the Latvian Gambit @@StartBracket@@2...f5@@EndBracket@@ and the more serious Elephant Gambit @@StartBracket@@2...d5@@EndBracket@@. The Philidor with 2...d6 is also effectively countered. For completeness sake, 2...f6, 2...Qe7, and 2...Qf6 are also covered.   Finally, the Nimzowitsch Defense with 1...Nc6 is also tackled. This hypermodern opening is better than it looks and White needs to be quite precise to obtain an advantage. I was unable to find a sizeable advantage with the natural 2. d4 and therefore chose to recommend 2. Nf3.   This repertoire has been designed from the ground up to be practical and easy to learn. To this point, I have used theImportant lines feature and added aQuickstarter with a selection of the 12 most important lines.   As in all of my courses, you can count on a high level of support. I will promptly answer any questions you have and regularly update the course with new theoretical developments.  That's all for the intro, I hope you enjoy the course and score many points with this repertoire! }
