1. e4 e5
{ 1...Nc6  2.Nf3  Nf6  This Alekhine-like knight sortie was recommended in the book 'Play 1... Nc6!' by Christoph Wisnewski. The specific clash occurshere where White can count on a big advantage. The more logical  2...d6  was recommended in the book 'The Modernized Nimzovich Defense' by GM Christian Bauer. Clickhere for the specific clash. }
2. Nf3 Nf6
{ 2...d5  was recommended in the book 'The Exhilarating Elephant Gambit' by IM Jakob Aabling-Thomsen and Michael Jensen for Quality Chess. The specific clash can be foundhere where White has a big edge. }
3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Bd6
{ 6...Nc6  7.O-O  Be7  8.Nbd2  was not considered in the book Opening Repertoire: The Petroff Defense by IM Cyrus Lakdawala nor in the book A Vigorous Chess Opening Repertoire for Black by FM Or Cohen.   8...Nxd2  9.Bxd2  Bg4  10.c3  O-O  11.h3  was not considered in the book The Petroff - an expert repertoire for Black by GM Konstantin Sakaev. Clickhere for the details.  8...Bf5  9.Re1  was not covered in Chessbase FritzTrainer The Reliable Petroff - An Evergreen Elite Choice by GM Daniel Fernandez. Check it outhere. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4 c6 9. Qc2 Na6 10. a3 Bg4
{ was recommended in the Chessable course 'Fight 1.e4 like Caruana' by IM Cristof Sielecki. I propose a key novelty on move 14 that was not considered in this course and gives White the upper hand. Clickhere for the details.   10...f5  was recommended in the book 'Playing the Petroff' by GM Swapnil Dhopade. I propose a very interesting, rare option on move 12 that was not considered in this book and gives White excellent chances for an advantage. Check it outhere.  I will regularly update this list as new literature is published. If there are any other specific repertoire book/database/course recommendations that you think I should address, please leave a comment below and I'll add them to this list. }
