{ Almost all the lines in the course are the result of original analysis with the latest versions of Stockfish and Leela running on very fast cloud servers.   I made extensive use of correspondence and high-level OTB games. I also paid close attention to the most popular replies at the club level by checking the Lichess online database.  Engines: latest versions of Stockfish and Leela Chess  Databases: MegaDatabase, CorrBase, Lichess database  Books/DVDs/Courses:  -Christian Bauer, The Modernized Nimzovich Defense, Thinkers Publishing, 2020  -Christoph Wisnewski, Play 1... Nc6!, Everyman Chess, 2007   -Christof Sielecki, Fight 1.e4 like Caruana, Chessable course  -Cyrus Lakdawala, Opening Repertoire: The Petroff Defense, Everyman Chess, 2019  -Daniel Fernandez, The Reliable Petroff - An Evergreen Elite Choice, Chessbase FritzTrainer, 2018  -Jakob Aabling-Thomsen and Michael Jensen, The Exhilarating Elephant Gambit, Quality Chess, 2020  -Konstantin Sakaev, The Petroff: An Expert Repertoire for Black, Chess Stars, 2011  -Or Cohen, A Vigorous Chess Opening Repertoire for Black, NewinChess, 2013  -Swapnil Dhopade, Playing the Petroff, Quality Chess, 2020  -Larry Kaufman, Kaufman's New Repertoire for Black and White, NewinChess, 2019  -Vassilios Kotronias and Andeas Tzermiadianos, Beating the Petroff, Batsford, 2004  I'd like to credit the latter for highlighting a few of the themes listed in the Key middlegame themes chapter. }
