[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "1...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The Nimzowitsch defense is an unusual, hypermodern opening. Black invites White to take over the center with d2-d4 with the intention of later undermining the central pawns with well-timed pawn breaks. However, we won't be allowing any such shenanigans. }
2. Nf3
{ is the simplest and most effective reply.   2.d4  is possible but White's chances for an advantage after  2...d5  are slim. }
2... d6 3. d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 Bg4
{ tries to put pressure on the d4 pawn by pinning the f3 knight. } 5. Be3 e6
{ Black wants to play ...d5 next, achieving a French-like position with his bishop outside the pawn chain. }
6. h3 Bh5
{ 6...Bxf3  is too cooperative.  7.Qxf3+=  White has the center and bishop pair. Next up is O-O-O followed by g4-g5 with a big advantage. }
7. d5
{ Exclam! White gains a lot of space and stops Black from liberating his position with ...d6-d5. }
7... exd5 8. exd5 Ne5 9. g4
{ Starts active play on the kingside. This makes perfect sense as we'll castle long. }
9... Bg6
{ 9...Nxf3+  10.Qxf3  Bg6  11.O-O-O±  White is almost fully developed while Black only has two minor pieces out. It's clear that White is much better. }
10. Nd2
{ clears the way for f4-f5 with a huge advantage. Black also needs to watch out for Bb5+ in certain variations.   A sample continuation is  10...h6  11.f4  Ned7  12.f5  Bh7  13.Qe2  Be7  14.O-O-O  O-O  15.h4↑  with a huge attack. Black's in big trouble. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...f5 Latvian Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f5
{ The Latvian Gambit, also known as the Greco Countergambit, is one of the oldest chess openings. We'll be outright refuting this unsound gambit. }
3. Nxe5
{ not only wins a pawn but clears the way for Qh5+. It's move 3 and Black is already in big trouble. }
3... Qf6 { is the only sensible follow-up. } 4. d4 d6 5. Nc4 fxe4
{ Black restores material equality but the pawn on e4 is a target, the bishop on f8 is restricted, and Black's queen is completely misplaced. }
6. Nc3 Qg6 7. Ne3
{ covers the g2 pawn in order to develop the light-squared bishop. } 7... Nf6
8. Be2 Be7 { allows White to jump in with } 9. Ncd5
{ immediately going for the throat and hitting c7. } 9... Bd8
{ 9...Nxd5??  blunders the queen to  10.Bh5+− } 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. O-O
{ White is now ready to break with f2-f3. } 11... Qe7
{ Getting off the f-file does no good: } 12. f3
{ All of Black's pieces occupy the back rank except the queen. White, on the other hand, is almost fully mobilized and ready to open up the position. Black is far too undeveloped to survive this.   A sample continuation is  12.f3  O-O  13.fxe4  Rxf1+  14.Qxf1  Now  14...Qxe4??  is tempting but drops a piece to  15.Bc4+  Be6  16.Qd3!  Qxd3  17.Bxe6+  Intermezzo!  17...Kh8  18.cxd3+- }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...d5 Elephant Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ The Elephant Gambit. @@StartBlockQuote@@Any opening named after an animal is not very good. - GM Sam Shankland@@EndBlockQuote@@While this is no exception, this gambit is very tricky and White needs to be precise to emerge with an advantage while minimizing Black's counterplay. }
3. exd5 Bd6
{ is less common than  3...e4  but objectively stronger. It was recently recommended in the book The Exhilarating Elephant Gambit by IM Jakob Aabling-Thomsen and Michael Jensen so I expect it to increase in popularity. }
4. d4 e4 5. Nfd2
{ Our knight is forced back but this is only temporary. Apart from hitting the e4 pawn, it's also headed to c4 to attack Black's bishop. }
5... Nf6 { is Black's most popular move. } 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3
{ is the simplest route towards a big advantage.   7.Be2  is another good option.  7...b5   7...c6  runs into the novel and strong  8.c5  N  Bf4  9.d6  e3  10.fxe3  Bxe3  11.Nc4  Bxc1  12.Qxc1+-  with an overwhelming position.  8.cxb5  a6  9.Nc3  axb5  10.Bxb5±  White is objectively much better here but Black does have some play. This is the main reason I opted for 7. Nc3, which reduces Black's activity to a minimum. }
7... Bb4 8. Be2 { takes firm control over the g4 square. } 8... c6 9. Qb3
{ Reinforces the d5 pawn while hitting Black's bishop. } 9... Na6
{ 9...Bxc3  10.bxc3  cxd5  11.cxd5  Nxd5  recoups the d5 pawn but drops the one on e4 to  12.Nxe4± }
10. O-O Re8 11. Re1
{ Next up are Nf1-e3 and Bf4 with a clear advantage. Black is still a pawn down and his pieces are scattered all over the board.   A sample continuation is  11.Re1  h6!  is Black's best move but he still has a lot of problems after  12.Nf1  cxd5  13.Bf4  Bxc3  14.bxc3  dxc4  15.Bxc4  Be6  16.Ne3  Bxc4  17.Nxc4  Qd7  18.Be5±  with a clear advantage. White has superior central control, the pawn on e4 is weak, and the bishop on e5 is a big asset. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2...d6 Philidor"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ is known as the Philidor defense, which derives its name from the 18th-century French chess player and composer François-André Danican Philidor. Nowadays, this variation is regarded as quite passive and is rarely seen at the top level in classical time controls. That being said, top GMs like Carlsen and Dubov have occasionally essayed it in rapid and blitz tournaments. }
3. d4 exd4
{ Clarifying the tension in the center is by far Black's main move. } 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7
{ is known as the Antonishin variation and is Black's most popular continuation. }
6. Bf4
{ This has been established as White's best setup in correspondence chess. The idea is simple and aggressive: White intends Qd2 followed by O-O-O. }
6... O-O 7. Qd2 Nc6
{ Black wants to swap off a pair of knights, which is a sensible strategy given he has a space disadvantage. }
8. O-O-O Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Be6 10. f3
{ g4 and h4 are coming next with a big attack. This will be much faster than any counterplay Black can muster up with ...a6 + ...b5.  Chessable note: please refer to themain section of the course for further analysis. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "3...Nc6 Stafford Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ characterizes the Petroff defense. This opening, which is also known as the Russian defense, has a reputation for being rock-solid and has been the choice of several top-GMs such as Anand, Karpov, Kramnik, and Caruana in multiple World-Championship matches and Candidates tournaments. }
3. Nxe5 Nc6
{ is the infamous Stafford gambit, which was popularized by IM Eric Rosen and other well-known streamers.  @@StartBlockQuote@@The Stafford Gambit is the trappiest opening in chess. - IM Eric Rosen@@EndBlockQuote@@Why did it become so popular? Here are some of the frequent traps White has fallen into.   4.Nxc6  dxc6  5.e5  Ne4  6.d3??  is natural but already losing to  6...Bc5  7.dxe4  when  7...Bxf2  wins White's queen.  8.Kxf2  Qxd1−+  while  8.Ke2  still loses to  8...Bg4−+   Another common trick is  4.Nxc6  dxc6  5.d3  Bc5  Here the natural  6.Bg5??  runs into  6...Nxe4!  7.Bxd8  7...Bxf2  is mate and has occurred well over 700 times on Lichess! Note  7.Qe2  doesn't lose outright but Black is still winning after  7...Qxg5  8.Qxe4  Kd8!  clearing the way for ...Re8!  9.Be2  Qc1  10.Bd1  Re8−+   Yet another one is  4.Nxc6  dxc6  5.Nc3  Bc5  6.Bc4?  is another natural move that runs into trouble on f2 after  6...Ng4  when  7.O-O?  loses to  7...Qh4  8.h3  Nxf2  crashing through. For example  9.Qf3  Nxh3  10.Kh1  Nf2  11.Kg1  Qh1  is mate!  We'll avoid all the tricks and easily put it out of business with }
4. Nxc6 dxc6
{ is the correct recapture, opening up the light-squared bishop. Despite being a pawn down, Black is ahead in development which partly explains why he has occasionally had success in online games. }
5. e5 { White has several good options here but this is the most incisive. }
5... Ne4
{ is Black's only way of creating counterplay. He intends to follow up with ...Qh4 and ...Bc5, honing in on the f2 pawn. }
6. d4 { Black can move in with } 6... Qh4
{ But White is very well equipped to deal with this queen sortie. Here } 7. Qe2
{ The only way to keep the knight alive is to retreat with } 7... Ng5
{ but after } 8. Be3 Bf5 9. Nd2
{ Black is not only a pawn down but his pieces lack coordination. White is now threatening to win the knight with g3 followed by h4. }
9... Ne4
{ Removes the knight from danger.   9...Bxc2??  blunders the knight to  10.g3  Qh6  11.h4+- }
10. g3 Qd8 11. Bg2
{ forces the knight to move for the 5th time. Out of 11 moves, Black has moved his knight 5 times and the queen twice. Needless to say, Black is in dire straits. }
11... Nxd2 12. Qxd2 Be7 13. O-O
{ gives White a decisive advantage. Black has zero compensation for the pawn deficit and lack of central control. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Petroff 3...Nxe4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ characterizes the Petroff defense. This opening, which is also known as the Russian defense, has a reputation for being rock-solid and has been the choice of several top-GMs such as Anand, Karpov, Kramnik, and Caruana in multiple World-Championship matches and Candidates tournaments. }
3. Nxe5 { The Classical variation is my recommendation. } 3... Nxe4
{ is very dubious as Black will be in trouble along the e-file. } 4. Qe2 Qe7
{ Blocking the e-file. Black is not sacrificing the piece here as after } 5.
Qxe4 d6 { he'll be able to recoup the knight. } 6. d4
{ Reinforces the knight on e5 and opens up the dark-squared bishop. Black can regain the pawn with accurate play but will never come close to equalizing. }
6... dxe5 7. dxe5 Nc6 8. Nc3
{ is the simplest route towards a big advantage. We give back the extra pawn in exchange for piece activity. }
8... Qxe5 9. Qxe5+ Nxe5 10. Nb5 { Black has no good way to cover the c7 pawn. }
10... Bd6
{ 10...Kd8  leaves the king very exposed. After  11.Bf4  f6  12.O-O-O+±  White is clearly for choice.   10...Bb4+  is analyzed in themain section of the course. }
11. Nxd6+ cxd6 12. Be3
{ is much better for White. The d6 pawn is about to be targeted with O-O-O, not to mention we have the two bishops. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Petroff 6...Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Bg4
{ Prioritizing development of the queenside pieces cannot be recommended. } 7.
h3 { Immediately puts the question to the bishop. } 7... Bh5 8. O-O Be7 9. c4
{ is accurate, striking in the center to destabilize Black's knight. This is especially effective here given Black's king is still in the center.   Furthermore, it opens up the possibility of Qb3 to hit the b7 pawn, which has been left unprotected by Black's early bishop sortie. }
9... c6 { immediately runs into trouble after } 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Qb3
{ when Black has no good way of defending the b7 pawn. This highlights one of the big drawbacks of Black's bishop excursion.   A sample continuation is  11...O-O  12.Qxb7  Qd7  13.Qxd7  Nxd7  14.Nbd2±  when Black has no compensation for the pawn deficit. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Petroff 6...Bf5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2, and/or Nbd2/Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Bf5
{ is connected with the idea of exchanging off the light-squared bishops with ...Nd6 later on. }
7. O-O Be7 8. Re1 O-O 9. Nbd2
{ Quickly undermining Black's e4 knight is my preference here.   9.c4  is also possible but White has been unable to put any pressure on Black's position.  9...Nc6  10.cxd5  Qxd5  11.Nc3  Nxc3  12.bxc3  Bxd3  13.Qxd3  Rae8  14.Bf4  Bd6  15.c4  Qh5  16.Bxd6  cxd6  17.Qa3  Qa5  18.Qxd6  Rxe1+  19.Rxe1=  All the OTB games that reached this position were effortlessly drawn. A few relatively recent examples are 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2761@@EndBracket@@-Wei,Y @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ Abidjan 2019, ½-½ @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2767@@EndBracket@@ -Wei,Y @@StartBracket@@2743@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2018 and ½-½ @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Naiditsch,A @@StartBracket@@2695@@EndBracket@@-Li,C @@StartBracket@@2691@@EndBracket@@ China 2019. }
9... Nd6
{ Following through with Black's original idea of trading the light-squared bishops.   9...Nxd2?!  hands over the bishop pair for no reason. After  10.Bxf5  Nxf3+  11.Qxf3±  White is threatening Qh3 and is clearly for choice. }
10. Nf1
{ Nb1-d2-f1 is a typical maneuver in this structure. The knight can later head to g3, hitting the f5 bishop, or e3 to pressure the d5 pawn depending on how Black proceeds. }
10... Bxd3
{ 10...Nd7  is another possible move order.  11.Bf4  Bxd3  12.Qxd3  Re8  13.Qb3+=  transposes   10...c6  11.Bf4  Bxd3  12.Qxd3  also transposes to the text. }
11. Qxd3
{ Let's take stock. The pawn structure is symmetrical but White's pieces are better placed, which gives us a slight advantage.  The dark-squared bishop is coming to f4, which will be more active than Black's bishop on e7. Our queen is headed to b3 to pressure the d5 and b7 pawns and is more active than Black's queen.  Finally, the f1 knight is headed to e3 while Black's b8 knight still occupies the starting square. }
11... Nd7 12. Bf4
{ is typically the best square for the bishop, where it's most active. } 12...
Re8 13. Qb3 { The only way to cover both pawns is } 13... Nb6 14. a4
{ is a typical move, gaining space on the queenside and intending to push back Black's pieces with a5. White can also consider expanding on the other side of the board with h4 later on. Black is quite solid but lacks an active plan.   White had slightly better chances, going on to win in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Dominguez Perez,L @@StartBracket@@2758@@EndBracket@@-Duda,J @@StartBracket@@2743@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021. This game is analyzed in themodel games chapter. }
*

