[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Petroff 6...Nc6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Nc6
{ is Black's most popular move. The second player opts to pressure our d4 pawn instead of worrying about the knight on e4. Another point behind Black's knight placement is to meet c4 with ...Nb4. }
7. O-O Be7
{ is Black's most popular move and the absolute main line of the Petroff. } 8.
Nbd2
{ is the modern main line and a very practical choice. It has far less theory than the more common alternatives 8. c4 and 8. Re1 and gives White larger chances for an advantage. }
8... Nxd2 { is at least 4x more common than the alternatives. } 9. Bxd2 Bg4
{ Black can also start with  9...O-O  10.c3  Bg4  which transposes to the text. }
10. c3
{ severely restricts Black's knight on c6 and clears the way for Qb3 later on. }
10... O-O 11. h3
{ Prepares to break the annoying pin. This move was not covered in the book The Petroff - an expert repertoire for White by GM Konstantin Sakaev. }
11... Bh5 12. g3
{ is a common way of dealing with the pin along the d1-h5 diagonal. White wants to edge the king up to g2, covering the knight on f3, in order to develop the queen to c2. }
12... Qd7 { 12...Bg6  13.Qc2  Qd7  14.Kg2  has little independent value. } 13.
Kg2 Bg6
{ 13...Rfe8  is also possible. After  14.Re1  Bd6  15.Qb3  15...Ne7  16.Nh4+=  White is slightly better and can double-up on the e-file with Re3 and Rae1 next. }
14. Bxg6 { is a good time to capture on g6, weakening Black's structure. }
14... hxg6 15. Bf4
{ Gives White a slight and stable advantage. We can continue with Qd3 and then expand on the kingside with h4-h5 supported by Rh1.    Chessable note: For more details, check out the followingvariation in the main theory section of the course. }
