[White "Key middlegame themes"]
[Black "Knight on e5"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbq1rk1/pp2bppp/2p2n2/8/2BP4/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ One of Black's main strategic concepts is anchoring the knight on e4 with the move ...d6-d5. This, however, weakens the e5 square.   Although not always critical, if Black fails to maintain the knight on e4 and is forced to retreat it to f6 or exchange it off, then White can often take over the e-file and install a knight on e5.   Black often cannot afford to let White's knight stay on e5, frequently exchanging it off with ...Nd7xe5. White then has the possibility of recapturing with the d-pawn creating a pawn majority on the kingside. When this majority becomes mobile and White can march ahead with f4-f5, Black is usually in a lot of trouble.   In the game 1-0  (60)  Zatonskih,A  (2432)  -Lagno,K  (2185)  Kramatorsk 2001, White immediately pounced with }
11. Ne5
{ The knight is very powerful here, exerting a lot of pressure on Black's position. }
11... Nbd7 12. Qb3
{ The pressure on the f7 pawn now forces Black to eliminate the knight with }
12... Nxe5 { when } 13. dxe5
{ gains space and pushes back Black's knight. Not only that, White intends to follow up with f4-f5. }
13... Ne8
{ The more active  13...Ng4  was a better option. White should protect the pawn with  14.Bf4  but not  14.f4?  which runs into  14...Bc5  15.Kh1  Qh4  with a mating attack. The point is  16.h3  Qg3  17.hxg4  Qh4  is game over }
14. Be3 b5 15. Be2 b4 16. Na4 Qa5 17. f4
{ activated White's kingside majority. The e and f-pawn duo can easily roll forward and create a lot of weaknesses around Black's king with f5-f6. White can also consider creating a dangerous passed pawn with e5-e6. }
*

