[Black "2...f6 Damiano's defense #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f6
{ Damiano's defense breaks almost every single opening principle and can be immediately punished with }
3. Nxe5 { The knight on e5 is basically untouchable as Qh5+ is a big threat. }
3... Qe7 { renders Qh5 ineffective but fails to help Black. } 4. Nf3
{ allows Black to recoup the e-pawn but Be2, O-O and Re1 are coming very fast.   4.Qh5+?  is a mistake.  4...g6  5.Nxg6  would be good if not for  5...Qxe4+  6.Be2  Qxg6-+  winning a piece. }
4... Qxe4+ 5. Be2 d5 6. O-O
{ Let's take stock: White's kingside is fully developed and Re1 is coming next. Black has no development and is unsurprisingly already dead lost. For example }
6... Ne7 7. Re1 Nbc6 8. Nc3 Qf5 9. d4
{ with ideas of Bd3 and Nb5 is already close to decisive. Black will find it impossible to complete development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. 2nd move sidelines [inc. Latvian & Elephant Gambits]"]
[Black "2...Qe7 Gunderam defense #1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Qe7
{ is the Gunderam defense, also known as the Brazilian defense. It is seldomly played and for good reason. Developing the Queen to e7 is not a good way of covering the e5 pawn. The queen is completely misplaced here, blocking in the bishop on f8. }
3. Bc4 d6 4. O-O
{ White's kingside is fully developed while Black's pieces still occupy the starting blocks. }
4... Nf6
{ Fianchettoing the bishop with  4...g6  doesn't change White's plan. After  5.d4  Bg7  6.dxe5  dxe5  7.Ng5±  Black has big problems. }
5. d4 c6
{ 5...Nxe4  runs into trouble along the e-file after  6.dxe5  dxe5  7.Re1+- }
6. c3 { Ng5 is now a big threat so Black should play } 6... h6
{ 6...Nxe4  is once again bad. After  7.Re1  d5  8.Bd3  The e4 knight will now drop.  8...Bg4  9.Bxe4  dxe4  10.Rxe4±  Not only restoring material equality, but White will also pick up the e5 pawn very soon. }
7. Re1 Nbd7 8. Nbd2 g6 9. b3
{ Prepares to bring out the bishop to a3, lining it up against Black's queen. }
9... Bg7 10. Ba3
{ White is now threatening to win material with dxe5 exploiting the fact that the d6 pawn is pinned. }
10... c5 11. b4
{ breaks down Black's construction. Black is ill-equipped to deal with this as he's still several moves away from completing development. White, on the other hand, is fully developed and clearly for choice. }
*

