1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Qe7
{ is the Gunderam defense, also known as the Brazilian defense. It is seldomly played and for good reason. Developing the Queen to e7 is not a good way of covering the e5 pawn. The queen is completely misplaced here, blocking in the bishop on f8. }
3. Bc4 h6
{ has also been played a few hundred times. White should continue with } 4. O-O
{ and is now ready to break with d4 next. } 4... Nf6 5. d4 d6
{ 5...Nxe4?  is strongly met by  6.Nxe5  Nd6  7.Re1+-  when Black is in big trouble along the e-file. }
6. Re1 Bg4 7. Nbd2 Nbd7
{ If Black grabs the pawn with  7...exd4  then  8.h3  Bh5   8...Bxf3  gives away the bishop pair.  9.Nxf3  Nbd7  10.Qxd4±  recoups the pawn with a clear advantage.  And now  8.c3!  is very strong. The point is that after  9...dxc3  10.bxc3  Nbd7  11.Ba3+−  Black is in big trouble with e4-e5 on the agenda. }
8. c3 g5 9. a4
{ The extra space and superior central control gave White a clear edge in the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Schwabeneder,F @@StartBracket@@2431@@EndBracket@@ -Breneis,L @@StartBracket@@2257@@EndBracket@@ Playchess.com INT 2020. }
