1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Qf6
{ is known as McConnell's or Greco's defense. Just like 2... Qe7, the queen on f6 is completely misplaced, this time occupying the g8 knight's best square. }
3. Nc3 c6
{ 3...Nc6  is hardly any better. Following  4.Bc4  d6  5.d4  Nxd4  6.Nxd4  exd4  7.Nb5  Qe7  8.O-O  ±  White has a big initiative. The immediate threat is Bg5 distracting Black's queen from the protection of the c7 pawn. }
4. d4 { challenges Black's e-pawn and opens up the dark-squared bishop. } 4...
exd4
{ 4...d6  drops material to  5.Bg5  Qg6  6.dxe5+-  Black cannot capture the e5 pawn due to the mate threat of Qd8. }
5. Bg5 Qg6 6. Qxd4 h6 7. Bf4 d6 8. O-O-O
{ White has an overwhelming position. The pawn on d6 is hanging and Nh4, as well as Bd3, are coming next. }
