[White "1. 2nd move sidelines [inc. Latvian & Elephant Gambits]"]
[Black "2...f5 Latvian Gambit #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f5
{ The Latvian Gambit, also known as the Greco Countergambit, is one of the oldest chess openings. We'll be outright refuting this unsound gambit. }
3. Nxe5
{ not only wins a pawn but clears the way for Qh5+. It's move 3 and Black is already in big trouble. }
3... Qf6
{ is the only sensible follow-up.   3...Nf6  is strongly met by  4.Bc4  Qe7  5.d4  Cementing the knight on e5.  5...Nc6  6.O-O  fxe4  Now  7.Ng4  is very strong. The point is that  7...d5  8.Nxf6+  Qxf6  9.Bxd5  wins a pawn. Following  9...Bf5  10.Be3  O-O-O  11.Nc3+−  Black has zero compensation for the pawn. }
4. d4 d6 5. Nc4 fxe4
{ Black restores material equality but the pawn on e4 is a target, the bishop on f8 is restricted and Black's queen is completely misplaced. }
6. Nc3 Qg6 7. Ne3
{ covers the g2 pawn in order to develop the light-squared bishop. } 7... Nf6
8. Be2 Be7 { allows White's knight to jump in with } 9. Ncd5
{ immediately going for the throat and hitting c7. } 9... Bd8 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6
11. O-O { Next up is f3 to open the position. } 11... Qe7
{ Getting off the f-file does no good: } 12. f3
{ All of Black's pieces occupy the back rank except the queen. White, on the other hand, is almost fully mobilized and ready to open up the position. Black is far too undeveloped to survive this.   A sample continuation is  12.f3  O-O  13.fxe4  Rxf1+  14.Qxf1  Now  14...Qxe4??  is tempting but drops a piece to  15.Bc4+  Be6  16.Qd3!  Qxd3  17.Bxe6+  Kh8  18.cxd3+- }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. 2nd move sidelines [inc. Latvian & Elephant Gambits]"]
[Black "2...f5 Latvian Gambit #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f5
{ The Latvian Gambit, also known as the Greco Countergambit, is one of the oldest chess openings. We'll be outright refuting this unsound gambit. }
3. Nxe5
{ not only wins a pawn but clears the way for Qh5+. It's move 3 and Black is already in big trouble. }
3... Qf6 { is the only sensible follow-up. } 4. d4 d6 5. Nc4 fxe4
{ Black restores material equality but the pawn on e4 is a target, the bishop on f8 is restricted and Black's queen is completely misplaced. }
6. Nc3 Qg6 7. Ne3
{ covers the g2 pawn so as to develop the light-squared bishop. } 7... Nf6 8.
Be2 c6 { Stops Ncd5 but spends yet another tempo moving a pawn. } 9. O-O
{ White is almost fully developed while most of Black's pieces are still on the back rank. Next up is f3 to open up the position. }
9... Be7 10. f3 O-O
{ 10...exf3  only helps White activate his pieces with  11.Bd3  Qh5  12.Rxf3+- }
11. fxe4 Nxe4 12. Bd3 { Pinning and winning at least a pawn following... }
12... Rxf1+ 13. Qxf1 d5 14. Qf3 { Piling on the e4 knight. } 14... Be6 15. Nxe4
dxe4 16. Bxe4
{ picks up a pawn with a winning position. Black has no compensation for the material deficit.   That's all you need to know about the Latvian Gambit, which is completely unsound. }
