[Black "2...d5 Elephant Gambit #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ The Elephant Gambit. @@StartBlockQuote@@Any opening named after an animal is not very good. - GM Sam Shankland@@EndBlockQuote@@While this is no exception, this gambit is very tricky and White needs to be precise to emerge with an advantage while minimizing Black's counterplay. }
3. exd5 Qxd5 { is a terrible version of the Scandinavian. } 4. Nc3 Qa5
{ 4...Qe6  runs into  5.Bb5+  c6  6.Ba4±  followed by Bb3, which will win another tempo on Black's queen, and O-O. White is clearly better.   4...Qd6  is strongly met by  5.Bb5  c6  6.Bc4±  with a big advantage. Next up is Qe2 to attack the e5 pawn.   Finally  4...Qc5  5.d4  exd4  6.Nxd4±  followed by Be3 will gain another tempo on Black's queen, further extending White's already significant lead in development. }
5. Bc4 Be7 6. Qe2 Nc6
{ 6...Nd7?!  is not very good but has been played. White should continue with  7.O-O  Ngf6  8.d4  exd4  9.Nb5  a6  when  10.Bd2!  is decisive. For example  10...axb5  11.Bxf7+  Kxf7  12.Bxa5  Rxa5  Black has three pieces for the queen but is too undeveloped and his king comes under a vicious attack after  13.Ng5+  Ke8  14.Rfe1  Nd5  15.Qh5+  g6  16.Qh6+-  Black won't survive this. }
7. Bb5
{ wins material as there's no saving the e5 pawn.   For example  7...Bg4  8.Bxc6+  bxc6  9.Qxe5  Qxe5+  10.Nxe5+-  is decisive.   7...f6  is also no solution. Apart from drastically weakening Black's position, it runs into problems after  8.a3  intending to go after Black's queen with b2-b4. For example  8...Bd7  9.Rb1  O-O-O  10.b4  Qb6  11.Nd5+−  wins Black's queen. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. 2nd move sidelines [inc. Latvian & Elephant Gambits]"]
[Black "2...d5 Elephant Gambit #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ The Elephant Gambit. @@StartBlockQuote@@Any opening named after an animal is not very good. - GM Sam Shankland@@EndBlockQuote@@While this is no exception, this gambit is very tricky and White needs to be precise to emerge with an advantage while minimizing Black's counterplay. }
3. exd5 e4 { makes little sense as after } 4. Qe2
{ Black's e4 pawn will eventually drop with d3 and Nbd2 coming next. } 4... Nf6
{ 4...Qe7  is very rare and for good reason. After  5.Nd4  Nf6  6.Nc3  Nbd7  7.Nf5  Qe5  8.Ng3  Nxd5  9.Ngxe4±  picks up a pawn. }
5. d3 Bb4+ { White should simply block with } 6. c3
{ when the only line worth remembering is } 6... O-O
{ The bishop on c5 is taboo since ...Re8 is coming fast. Black's problem is that White can block the e-file with }
7. dxe4 { The bishop is now hanging so Black should play } 7... Bc5 8. Bg5 Re8
9. Nbd2 { Reinforces the e4 pawn. } 9... h6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ At first sight, it may look like Black has some compensation for the two pawn deficit. This would be true if not for }
11. e5 { with the point that after } 11... Qb6 12. b4
{ forces Black's bishop all the way back to its starting square. } 12... Bf8
13. Qe4
{ clears the way for Bd3 with the devastating threat of Qh7+. White will then castle short and Black will have nothing to show for the pawn deficit.   For example  13...c6  trying to open up the position can simply be bypassed with  14.d6  which drops the d6 pawn to  14...Bxd6  but White has the tactical resource  15.Nc4  Qc7  16.Bd3  Qh7+ is now a huge threat so  16...f5  is forced. After  17.Qe2  Bf8  18.O-O+−  White has an extra pawn and a decisive positional advantage. }
