[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ The Elephant Gambit. @@StartBlockQuote@@Any opening named after an animal is not very good. - GM Sam Shankland@@EndBlockQuote@@While this is no exception, this gambit is very tricky and White needs to be precise to emerge with an advantage while minimizing Black's counterplay. }
3. exd5 Bd6
{ is less common than 3...e4 but objectively stronger. It was recently recommended in the book The Exhilarating Elephant Gambit by Michael Agermose Jensen and Jakob Aabling-Thomsen so I expect it to increase in popularity. }
4. d4 e4 5. Nfd2
{ Our knight is forced back but this is only temporary. Apart from hitting the e4 pawn, it's also headed to c4 to attack Black's bishop. }
5... f5 6. Nc4
{ intends to chop off Black's bishop and then reinforce the d5 pawn with c2-c4. }
6... Bb4+ { makes little sense as } 7. c3 { forces it back. After } 7... Be7 8.
Qa4+ Nd7 9. Bf4
{ White is threatening to push ahead with d5-d6 and is clearly better. } *

