[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ The Elephant Gambit. @@StartBlockQuote@@Any opening named after an animal is not very good. - GM Sam Shankland@@EndBlockQuote@@While this is no exception, this gambit is very tricky and White needs to be precise to emerge with an advantage while minimizing Black's counterplay. }
3. exd5 Bd6
{ is less common than 3...e4 but objectively stronger. It was recently recommended in the book The Exhilarating Elephant Gambit by Michael Agermose Jensen and Jakob Aabling-Thomsen so I expect it to increase in popularity. }
4. d4 e4 5. Nfd2
{ Our knight is forced back but this is only temporary. Apart from hitting the e4 pawn, it's also headed to c4 to attack Black's bishop. }
5... f5 6. Nc4 Be7 7. Qh5+ g6 8. Qh3
{ The queen is very well placed on h3. We're ready to jump in with Ne5 to threaten Nxg6. It may look exposed to ...f4, opening up Black's light-squared bishop, but we can just swing the queen over to b3 if required. }
8... Nf6 9. Ne5 { Threatens Nxg6 and clears the c4 square for Bc4. } 9... Nxd5
10. Bc4 { 10.Nxg6  f4  gives Black unnecessary counterplay. } 10... Nc6
{ is practically forced. The alternatives below lead to an outright lost position.   10...f4?  11.Qb3+-  is lights out.   10...Bb4+  11.c3  f4  doesn't do anything. White can just play  12.g4+-  when Nxg6 is a huge threat. Black is busted.   10...O-O  fails to  11.Qb3  c6  12.Nc3+-  The pin will net White at least a pawn. }
11. Nxg6 Nxd4 12. O-O
{ is ruthless. Black will end up clearly worse and without any practical chances.   12.Nxh8  Nxc2+  13.Kf1  Bh4  14.Nc3±  While White is objectively much better, this gives Black more chances for counterplay. I see no reason to allow Black any play based around ...f4 or ...Nde3+. }
12... f4 13. Qh5 { Threatening all kinds of deadly discoveries. After } 13...
Nf6 14. Qh4 Nf5 15. Qg5
{ The knights' tango has finished and Black is out of moves.   A sample continuation is  15.Qg5  h6  16.Qxf4  Bd6  17.Qd2  Rh7  18.f3+-  with an extra pawn and an overwhelming position. }
