1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ The Elephant Gambit. @@StartBlockQuote@@Any opening named after an animal is not very good. - GM Sam Shankland@@EndBlockQuote@@While this is no exception, this gambit is very tricky and White needs to be precise to emerge with an advantage while minimizing Black's counterplay. }
3. exd5 Bd6
{ is less common than 3...e4 but objectively stronger. It was recently recommended in the book The Exhilarating Elephant Gambit by IM Jakob Aabling-Thomsen and Michael Agermose Jensen and so I expect it to increase in popularity. }
4. d4 e4 5. Nfd2 { Covering the e4 pawn and clearing the way for ...O-O with }
5... Nf6 { is Black's most popular move. } 6. c4 O-O 7. Nc3
{ is the simplest route towards a big advantage.   7.Be2  is another good option.  7...b5   7...c6  runs into the novel and strong  8.c5  N  Bf4  9.d6  e3  10.fxe3  Bxe3  11.Nc4  Bxc1  12.Qxc1+-  with an overwhelming position.  8.cxb5  a6  9.Nc3  axb5  10.Bxb5±  White is objectively much better here but Black does have some play. This is the main reason I opted for 7. Nc3, which reduces Black's activity to a minimum. }
7... Bb4
{ 7...Re8  has also been tried. The treatment is similar to the mainline  8.Be2  Bb4  9.O-O  c6  10.dxc6  Nxc6  11.Nb3+-  when Black has nothing to show for the material deficit. }
8. Be2 { takes firm control over the g4 square. } 8... c6 9. Qb3
{ Reinforces the d5 pawn while attacking Black's bishop. } 9... Na6
{ 9...Bxc3  10.bxc3  cxd5  11.cxd5  Nxd5  recoups the d5 pawn but drops the one on e4 to  12.Nxe4± }
10. O-O Re8 11. Re1
{ Next up are Nf1-e3 and Bf4 with a clear advantage. Black is still a pawn down and his pieces are scattered all over the board.   A sample continuation is  11.Re1  h6!  is Black's best move but he still has a lot of problems after   Worse is  11...cxd5  12.cxd5+-  12.Nf1  cxd5  13.Bf4  Bxc3  14.bxc3  dxc4  15.Bxc4  Be6  16.Ne3  Bxc4  17.Nxc4  Qd7  18.Be5±  gives White a clear advantage and was not considered in the book The Exhilarating Elephant Gambit by IM Jakob Aabling-Thomsen and Michael Jensen. White has superior central control, the pawn on e4 is weak, and the bishop on e5 is a big asset. }
*

