1. e4 e5
{ 1...d6  2.d4  Nf6  3.Nc3  e5  is the modern way to reach the Philidor, which is covered in detail in the course Crush the Pirc, Modern and Philidor! @@LinkStart@@https://www.chessable.com/crush-the-pirc-modern-philidor/course/45966/@@LinkEnd@@. }
2. Nf3 d6
{ This chapter is dedicated to the Philidor defense, which derives its name from the 18th-century French chess player and composer François-André Danican Philidor. Nowadays, this variation is regarded as quite passive and is rarely seen at the top level in classical time controls. That being said, top GMs like Carlsen and Dubov have occasionally essayed it in rapid and blitz tournaments. }
3. d4 { Here we will examine the following options: } 3... exd4
{ is Black's main move with 19000+ games.   3...Nf6  is second most common with 5600+ games.   3...Nd7  is third most popular with 5300+ games.   3...Bg4  is fourth most common with 2000+ games.   3...Nc6  was seen in 1300+ games.   3...f5  The Philidor Countergambit has featured in 600+ OTB games.   3...Qe7  has occurred in 500+ games. }
*

