1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor defense derives its name from the 18th-century French chess player and composer François-André Danican Philidor. Nowadays, this variation is regarded as quite passive and is rarely seen at the top level in classical time controls. That being said, top GMs like Carlsen and Dubov have occasionally essayed it in rapid and blitz tournaments. }
3. d4
{ If Black doesn't actively fight for control over the center @@StartBracket@@and specifically the d4 square@@EndBracket@@, we might as well take it over! }
3... Qe7
{ I was surprised to find this has been played well over 500 times given how misplaced Black's queen is on e7. }
4. Nc3 c6
{ Taking control over the key d5 square is most common. The main alternatives are considered below.   4...Nf6  can be simply met with  5.Bc4  c6  Note that the e4 pawn is untouchable as after   5...exd4  6.Nxd4  Nxe4  7.Nd5  lands Black in a world of trouble. For example  7...Qe5  8.f4+-  already traps Black's queen.  6.Be3  h6  7.a4  Nbd7  8.O-O  ±  is clearly better for White with d4-d5 in the cards. Black's queen on e7 is completely misplaced, blocking the bishop on f8. }
5. Bc4 h6
{ 5...Bg4  has also been played a few dozen times. After  6.Be3  Nd7  7.h3  improves over the correspondence game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Kizimenko, N @@StartBracket@@2338@@EndBracket@@-Contreras Poblete, J  @@StartBracket@@2300@@EndBracket@@ email 2010  7...Bxf3  8.Qxf3±  followed by O-O-O and g2-g4 with a clear advantage. }
6. O-O Nf6 7. a4
{ A typical pawn push in the Philidor, stopping any future ideas of ...b7-b5 and intending to gain even more space on the queenside with a4-a5. }
7... Qc7
{ is a clear admission the queen shouldn't have gone to e7 in the first place.   If  7...Bg4  then White should play  8.dxe5  dxe5  9.h3  Bh5  10.Qd3  10...Nbd7  11.Rd1±  followed by a5 gives White a clear advantage. Once again, Black would much rather have his queen on c7. }
8. a5 Be7 9. Nh4
{ is another typical maneuver, aiming to post the knight on f5 and clearing the way for the pawn break f2-f4. }
9... Na6
{ 9...Nbd7  allows us to jump in with  10.Nf5±   9...Nxe4??  blunders the game away to  10.Bxf7   10.Qh5  d5  11.Nxe4  dxc4  12.dxe5+−  is also winning  10...Kxf7  11.Qh5  Kg8  12.Nxe4+− }
10. dxe5 dxe5 11. f4
{ White was clearly better and went on to win a model game in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@ Adams, M @@StartBracket@@2740@@EndBracket@@ -Kurajica, B @@StartBracket@@2541@@EndBracket@@ Izmir 2004.   A sample continuation is  11...Nb4  and here Adams could have gained a decisive advantage with  12.fxe5  Qxe5  13.Kh1  Be6  14.Bf4  Qh5  15.Bxe6  fxe6  16.Qxh5  Nxh5  17.Ng6+− }
*

