1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor defense derives its name from the 18th-century French chess player and composer François-André Danican Philidor. Nowadays, this variation is regarded as quite passive and is rarely seen at the top level in classical time controls. That being said, top GMs like Carlsen and Dubov have occasionally essayed it in rapid and blitz tournaments. }
3. d4 f5
{ is the Philidor Countergambit, which is completely unsound. I was surprised to find it had been played by Bronstein and Radjabov. Without having developed any minor pieces, Black is not ready to challenge White's center in this fashion. }
4. Bc4 { The point is that } 4... fxe4 { is strongly met by } 5. Nxe5
{ The knight on e5 is untouchable as Qh5+ is coming next, not to mention that Bf7+ and Nf7 are also huge threats. }
5... d5 { 5...dxe5??  loses on the spot to  6.Qh5+  g6  7.Qxe5++- } 6. Qh5+ g6
7. Nxg6 hxg6
