1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor defense derives its name from the 18th-century French chess player and composer François-André Danican Philidor. Nowadays, this variation is regarded as quite passive and is rarely seen at the top level in classical time controls. That being said, top GMs like Carlsen and Dubov have occasionally essayed it in rapid and blitz tournaments. }
3. d4 f5
{ is the Philidor Countergambit, which is completely unsound. I was surprised to find it had been played by Bronstein and Radjabov. Without having developed any minor pieces, Black is not ready to challenge White's center in this fashion. }
4. Bc4
{ essentially refutes this gambit. The e4 pawn is hanging but Black is in no position to take it. }
4... exd4 5. O-O fxe4 6. Nxd4
{ Now Qh5+ is a big threat, which forces Black to play } 6... Nf6
{ 6...d5  7.Qh5++-  wins material. } 7. Nc3 c6
{ is the only move that has occurred in practice thus far.   7...d5  once again loses material to  8.Nxd5  Nxd5  9.Qh5+  g6  10.Qe5++-  which will pick up the rook on h8.   7...Be7  doesn't lose outright but after  8.Re1  Black has big problems along the e-file. }
8. Nxe4
{ is a beautiful tactical shot, exploiting Black's lack of development. } 8...
Nxe4 9. Re1 d5 10. Qh5+ { forces Black's king up the board. } 10... Kd7
{ 10...g6  loses on the spot to  11.Qe5++- } 11. Rxe4
{ Boom! White eliminates Black's only active piece and open's the d-file against Black's king, which is toast. }
11... dxe4 12. Bg5 Be7
{ 12...Qe8??  drops the queen to  13.Be6+  Kd6  14.Qxe8+- } 13. Ne6
{ Black's queen is hanging and Rd1 is also coming. Black is busted. } *

