1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Bg4 4. dxe5 Bxf3
{ 4...dxe5  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  6.Nxe5+−  Attacks the bishop on g4 and threatens Nxf7, not to mention White is already a pawn up. }
5. Qxf3 { Thanks for the bishop pair! } 5... dxe5 6. Qb3
{ Hitting the pawn on b7 and preparing Bc4.   The chess history aficionados will likely recall that  6.Bc4  was played in the game 1-0 Morphy, P - Duke of Brunswick Paris 1858 - one of the most famous games in chess history. The text is even stronger. }
6... b6 7. Bc4
{ Black's position is full of weaknesses on the light squares. White has a lead in development and the pair of bishops in an open position. Enough said. }
