1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor defense derives its name from the 18th-century French chess player and composer François-André Danican Philidor. Nowadays, this variation is regarded as quite passive and is rarely seen at the top level in classical time controls. That being said, top GMs like Carlsen and Dubov have occasionally essayed it in rapid and blitz tournaments. }
3. d4
{ If Black doesn't actively fight for the center, we might as well take it over! }
3... Nd7 { is Black's third most common move. } 4. Bc4
{ is a very strong move, which prevents Black from developing naturally. } 4...
c6 { is Black's only reasonable move. } 5. O-O Be7
{ Also possible is  5...exd4  6.Nxd4  Ngf6  7.Nc3  a5  8.a4  Be7  9.Nf5±  with a big White advantage. }
6. dxe5 dxe5 { And now } 7. Ng5 { creates a lot of problems for Black. } 7...
Bxg5
{ 7...Nh6  practically loses by force to the beautiful  8.Ne6!  fxe6  9.Bxh6  Nb6  is Black's only chance.   9...gxh6??  The bishop on h6 was taboo. White now checkmates by force with  10.Qh5+  Kf8  11.Bxe6  Qe8  12.Qxh6  After  10.Qh5+  g6  11.Qe2+−  Black's pawn structure is in tatters, granting White a decisive advantage. }
8. Qh5
{ This is the point behind 7...Bxg5. We recoup the piece due to the mate threat on f7. }
8... Qe7
{ 8...Qf6  isn't much better. After  9.Bxg5  Qg6  10.Qh4±  White had a clear advantage and went on to win in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@71@@EndBracket@@ Granda Zuniga, J @@StartBracket@@2630@@EndBracket@@-Rogers, I @@StartBracket@@2570@@EndBracket@@ New York 1998. }
9. Qxg5 Qxg5 10. Bxg5
{ This endgame is very favorable for White thanks to the bishop pair and lead in development. }
10... Nc5 11. f3 Be6 12. Nd2
{ This position was reached in four games where White scored 3.5/4.   A sample continuation is  12...b5  13.Be2  Na4  14.c4  a6  15.Rab1  with a clear advantage in the correspondence game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@58@@EndBracket@@ Luise, M -Aguirre Izaguirre, P IECG email 2004. }
