[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. 2...d6 Philidor"]
[Black "3...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ The Philidor defense derives its name from the 18th-century French chess player and composer François-André Danican Philidor. Nowadays, this variation is regarded as quite passive and is rarely seen at the top level in classic time controls. That being said, top-GMs like Carlsen and Dubov have occasionally essayed in rapid and blitz tournaments. }
3. d4 Nf6
{ is very suspect and the following continuation is the reason why Philidor players no longer use this move order. If Black wants to employ this setup, he should instead use the modern 1...d6 2...Nf6 3...e5 move order. }
4. dxe5 Nxe4
{ 4...dxe5?  blunders a pawn to  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  6.Nxe5  Be6  7.f3+− } 5. Qd5
{ The queen leaps into the game with almost decisive effect. The idea is to quickly develop the queenside with Bg5, Nc3, and then castle long. }
5... Nc5 6. Bg5 Qd7
{ This is Black's best, but something has clearly gone wrong if he has to resort to these kinds of moves.  Blocking with   6...Be7  results in a clear White advantage after the simple  7.exd6  cxd6  8.Nc3  h6  9.Bxe7  Qxe7+  10.Be2±  followed by O-O-O when the pawn on d6 is a big target. }
7. exd6 Bxd6 8. Nc3
{ White is almost fully mobilized, planning to complete development with O-O-O. }
8... O-O
{ If  8...Qe6+  then simply  9.Be3  Qxd5  10.Nxd5  Nbd7  11.Nd2  c6  12.Nc4  Bb8  13.Nc3  Ne6  14.O-O-O±  was clearly better for White in Yakovich, Y @@StartBracket@@2450@@EndBracket@@-Gabdrakhmanov, R Voronezh 1988. White can follow up with g3 and f4-f5. }
9. O-O-O Nc6 10. Nb5
{ White is much more active and the pin along the d-file is very annoying.   A sample continuation showcasing White's clear advantage is  10...Ne7  11.Qc4  Ne6  12.Bd3  Nxg5  13.Nxg5  h6  14.Qe4⭡  with a strong initiative. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
