[White "2. 2...d6 Philidor"]
[Black "3...Nc6 4...Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Nc6
{ is an interesting sideline. Black plans to pressure the d4 pawn with ...Bg4 next. }
4. Nc3 Bg4 { Pinning the knight and threatening exd4. } 5. Bb5
{ We reply in the same fashion! We're now threatening to win a pawn with Bxc6+ followed by dxe5. Trying to break the pin }
5... a6
{ is no good.   5...Bxf3?!  6.gxf3  White is now threatening d4-d5.  6...exd4  7.Bxc6+  bxc6  8.Qxd4  transposes to 5...exd4, which will be covered in thenext trainable line. }
6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. dxe5 Bxf3
{ 7...dxe5  8.Qxd8+  Rxd8  9.Nxe5+-  is a healthy extra pawn for White. Note that the knight on c3 covers the d1 square. }
8. Qxf3 dxe5 9. O-O
{ Black's pawn structure on the queenside is in shambles. White also has a big lead in development and is thus clearly better. Rd1 and Be3 are coming next. }
