[White "2. 2...d6 Philidor"]
[Black "3...Nc6 4...Bg4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Nc6
{ is an interesting sideline. Black plans to pressure the d4 pawn with ...Bg4 next. }
4. Nc3 Bg4 { Pinning the knight and threatening exd4. } 5. Bb5
{ We reply in the same fashion! We're now threatening to win a pawn with Bxc6+ followed by dxe5. }
5... exd4 6. Qxd4 Bxf3 7. Bxc6+
{ A nice intermediate move, spoiling Black's structure on the queenside. } 7...
bxc6 8. gxf3
{ White will develop the light-squared bishop to e3 or g5 and castle long. }
8... Nf6 9. Bg5 Be7 10. Qc4 { Tickling the c6 pawn. } 10... Qd7 11. O-O-O O-O
12. Rhg1
{ The semi-open g-file is a big asset in this position. White can combine play in the center with f4+e5 with an attack against Black's king.   Conversely, Black has less space and none of his pieces are on the queenside and so he won't be able to reach our king. White's advantage is undisputable. }
