[White "2. 2...d6 Philidor"]
[Black "3...Nc6 4...exd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Nc6 4. Nc3 exd4
{ is another option but not a particularly good one. } 5. Nxd4 g6
{ This variation carries the name of GM Simagin, who racked up a number of wins with 5...g6. However, }
6. Nd5
{ comes very close to refuting this variation. White is now threatening Nb5xc7 which is surprisingly hard to deal with. }
6... Nf6
{ is practically Black's only way of staying in the game. Alternatives are examined below.  Preventing Nb5 with   6...a6  fails to  7.Nxc6  bxc6  8.Qd4!  hitting the rook on h8.  8...f6  And now White has the stunning  9.Bc4!!  the point being that  9...cxd5  10.Qxd5+−  Threatens checkmate on f7 and attacks the rook on a8, with a winning position.   6...Nge7??  7.Nf6  Oops, that's checkmate!   The natural  6...Bg7  loses on the spot to  7.Nb5+−  as Black has no way of preventing Nxc7.   Finally  6...Nce7  also doesn't work due to the beautiful tactical shot  7.Nxc7+  Qxc7  8.Nb5  Qa5+  9.Bd2  Qd8  10.Bc3+−  when Black is defenseless against both Bxh8, and Nxd6 followed by Nxf7+. }
7. Bg5 Be7
{ 7...Bg7  8.Nb5+-  The c7 pawn will soon drop with a decisive advantage. } 8.
Nxe7 Qxe7 9. f3
{ White is now threatening Nxc6 followed by Qd4, which would pick up the knight on f6. }
9... h6
{ 9...O-O?  is strongly met by  10.Nxc6  bxc6  11.Qd4  pinning Black down. This forces  11...Kg7  when  12.O-O-O  Qe5  13.Be3  gives White an overwhelming position. The plan to drop back the queen with Qd4 and follow up with Bf4/h6 as well as h4-h5 is very strong. If  13...Kg8  stepping out of the pin then the simple  14.Qxe5  dxe5  15.Bc4+−  is good enough. Black's severely compromised pawn structure and White's bishop pair amount to an almost decisive advantage. }
10. Be3
{ White has more space, the pair of bishops and Black's kingside has a lot of weaknesses on the dark squares. Qd2 followed by O-O-O is coming next with a clear advantage. }
