[White "2. 2...d6 Philidor"]
[Black "3...Nc6 4...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Nc6 4. Nc3 Nf6 { is Black's third most common move. }
5. Bb5
{ Pins the knight, threatening to either win a piece with d5 or a pawn with dxe5. }
5... Bd7
{ 5...Bg4  loses material to  6.d5  Following  6...a6  7.Ba4  b5  8.Nxb5  axb5  9.Bxb5  Rb8  10.Bxc6+−  leaves White two pawns up. }
6. Bxc6 Bxc6 { 6...bxc6  drops the e5 pawn  7.dxe5  dxe5  8.Nxe5± } 7. Qd3
{ Defending the e4 pawn and renewing the threat of dxe5. } 7... exd4 8. Nxd4
{ White wants to develop to e3 and then castle long. } 8... Be7
{ is the best position for the bishop.   Alternatively  8...g6  runs into  9.Bg5  which is better than 9. Nxc6 played in the famous game 0-1 Nimzowitsch -Capablanca 1914. Following  9...Bg7  10.O-O-O  h6   The immediate  10...O-O?  runs into  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.e5!+-  11.Bh4  O-O  12.f4±  White is ready to break in the center with e5. He can also throw in Nxc6 at any moment with a clear advantage. }
9. f3 O-O 10. Be3
{ White will castle long and if Black does not strike in the center, then White can drum up a strong attack against Black's king by marching the h and g pawns up the board. }
10... d5 11. e5
{ Gaining even more space.   White can also enter a very favorable endgame with  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.O-O-O  White is now threatening dxe4 so Black should play  12...dxe4  13.Nxe4  13...Qxd3  14.Nxf6+  Bxf6  15.Rxd3±  Black's queenside pawns are incredibly weak. White is clearly better. }
11... Nd7 12. f4 Re8 13. O-O-O
{ Nf5 followed by h4 is coming next with a big advantage. Black's light-squared bishop is completely misplaced, preventing Black from challenging the center with ...c5 }
