[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 { An interesting sideline. } 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Bb5
{ Pinning the knight and threatening to win a pawn with dxe5. Pins the knight, threatening to win a pawn with dxe5. }
5... exd4 6. Qxd4
{ is the correct, recapture centralizing the queen. This allows White to push ahead with e4-e5 in certain positions. }
6... Bd7 7. Bxc6 Bxc6
{ The alternative recapture with  7...bxc6  makes little sense. After  8.O-O  Be7  9.e5  dxe5  10.Nxe5±  Rd1 is coming next with a clear advantage. Black's queenside structure is in ruins. }
8. Bg5 Be7 9. O-O-O O-O { And now White should break in the center with } 10.
e5 dxe5 11. Qxe5 Bd6 12. Qd4
{ Black has no good way of stopping Bxf6 which will spoil his kingside structure.   The following sample continuation with precise play by both sides is a good demonstration of White's advantage:  12...Re8  13.Bxf6  Qxf6  14.Qxf6  gxf6  15.Nd4!  is very precise. White drives back Black's bishop, taking advantage of the fact that the pawn on g2 is untouchable.  15...Bd7   15...Bxg2??  blunders the bishop to  16.Rdg1+−  16.Nd5  Kg7  17.g3⩲  Stopping ...Bf4. Ne3 and Nd4-f5 are coming next with a very pleasant endgame.   Worse is  12...Be7  because of  13.Qf4  unleashing the rook on d1 and vacating the d4 square for our knight.  13...Qc8  14.Nd4  Bd6  15.Qh4  Ng4  16.Nxc6  bxc6  17.h3±  gives White a clear advantage. Black has nothing to show for his compromised pawn structure. }
