[White "2. 2...d6 Philidor"]
[Black "3...exd4 5...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 exd4
{ Clarifying the tension in the center is by far Black's main move. } 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 g6
{ Developing the bishop to g7 is too slow and fails to give Black adequate counterplay. }
6. Be3
{ Clears the way for Qd2 and O-O-O. Black will then come under a massive kingside attack.   6.Bg5  is another good option. }
6... Bg7
{ 6...Ng4  only wastes valuable time as Black's knight will soon be forced back. For example  7.Bf4  Bg7  8.Qd2  Nc6  9.Nxc6  bxc6  10.f3  knocks the knight back.  10...Ne5  11.O-O-O  O-O  12.h4±  with the idea h4-h5 gives White a clear advantage. Be2 and Bh6 are also in the cards when White's kingside attack will be much faster than anything Black can drum up on the queenside. }
7. Qd2 O-O 8. O-O-O Re8 9. f3
{ This position resembles the Yugoslav Attack in the Sicilian Dragon. There is however one crucial difference. Here Black's pawn is on c7 instead of e7, and hence Black does not have the typical counterplay along the c-file. This means White's kingside attack with g4-h4 will be much faster. }
