1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 exd4
{ Clarifying the tension in the center is by far Black's main move. } 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7
{ is known as the Antonishin variation and is Black's most popular continuation. }
6. Bf4
{ This has been established as White's best setup in correspondence chess. The idea is both simple and aggressive: White intends Qd2 followed by O-O-O. }
6... O-O 7. Qd2 Nc6
{ This is Black's most popular move. He wants to swap off a pair of knights, which is a sensible strategy given he has a space disadvantage. }
8. O-O-O Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Be6 10. f3
{ g4 and h4 are on the agenda with a big attack. } 10... Nd7
{ clearing the way for ...Bf6 is Black's most common move. } 11. Qd2
{ Preempts Black's bishop coming to f6. White is now ready to start a pawn assault with h4 and g4. }
11... Bf6 12. h4 Rb8 13. g4 { White has a big headstart in this attack. } *

