[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 exd4
{ Clarifying the tension in the center is by far Black's main move. } 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7
{ is known as the Antonishin variation and is Black's most popular continuation. }
6. Bf4
{ This has been established as White's best setup in correspondence chess. The idea is both simple and aggressive: White intends Qd2 followed by O-O-O. }
6... O-O 7. Qd2 Nc6
{ This is Black's most popular move. He wants to swap off a pair of knights, which is a sensible strategy given he has a space disadvantage. }
8. O-O-O Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Be6 10. f3
{ g4 and h4 are coming next with a big attack. This will be much faster than any counterplay Black can muster up with ...a6 + ...b5. }
10... a6 11. g4 b5 12. h4
{ After Gerry, it's now Harry's time to move up the board. } 12... c5
{ And now White should retreat the queen to e3 } 13. Qe3
{ instead of d2, pinning the d-pawn. This is White's strongest move in this position, which was not considered in the aforementioned book. }
13... b4 14. Na4
{ White is now threatening Nxc5, taking advantage of the pin along the d-file. This is the main reason why 13. Qe3 is superior to 13. Qd2. }
14... Qc7
{ Getting out of the pin.   14...Bxa2??  15.b3  traps the bishop. Kb2 on the next turn will pick it up. }
15. b3 Nd7
{ 15...Bd7  runs into  16.g5  Nh5  and  17.Qxc5+-  A nice tactic, which nets White a pawn and a decisive advantage.   15...Qc6  intending to break in the center with ...d5 is too slow.  16.Rh2  Rfe8  17.h5  d5  18.g5  Nd7  19.g6±  when it's clear White's attack is much faster. }
16. h5
{ White is about to play h6 while Black's attack never got off the ground. Lifting the rook along the 2nd rank with Rh2-d2 to pressure the d6 pawn is also a typical maneuver to consider later on. }
