1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 exd4
{ Clarifying the tension in the center is by far Black's main move. } 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7
{ is known as the Antonishin variation and is Black's most popular continuation. }
6. Bf4
{ This has been established as White's best setup in correspondence chess. The idea is both simple and aggressive: White intends Qd2 followed by O-O-O. }
6... O-O 7. Qd2 d5
{ An attempt to create chaos on the board. Despite the sharp nature of the variations we're about to examine, this line has been worked out to a clear White advantage in correspondence chess. Nevertheless, precise knowledge of the following lines is necessary. }
8. Ndb5 { is a key move, threatening Nxc7 and exd5. } 8... Bb4
{ This is Black's only logical follow-up to 7... d5. Black pins the c3 knight and intends to continue with ...d4 and ...Nxe4.   Alternatively  8...Na6?!  covers c7 but simply drops the d5 pawn.  9.exd5  c6  10.d6  Re8  11.O-O-O  Bf8  12.Nd4±  White is a pawn up and is threatening Bxa6 followed by Nxc6. The d6 pawn is untouchable because of Nxc6. }
9. O-O-O
{ is important, stopping ...d4 and renewing the threat of Nxc7.   The hasty  9.Nxc7  is not very good as it runs into  9...d4∓ }
9... Nxe4 { is a big mistake on account of } 10. Qxd5 Qxd5 11. Nxd5
{ Attacking the bishop on b4. The pawn on c7 is also still hanging, effectively forcing }
11... Na6 12. Nxb4 Nxb4 13. Be3
{ is clearly better for White. The c7 pawn is hanging and a fork with Rd4 is also a big threat.   Black doesn't even have time for  13...Nxa2+?  as  14.Kb1  Nb4  15.Rd4+−  wins one of Black's knights.   Better is  13...c6  which is strongly met by  14.Rd4  which forks Black's knights, forcing  14...Nd5  15.Rxe4  Nxe3  16.Rxe3  cxb5  17.Bxb5+−  when White is a clean pawn up and thus close to winning. }
