{ This has been established as White's best setup in correspondence chess. The idea is both simple and aggressive: White intends Qd2 followed by O-O-O. }
6... O-O 7. Qd2 d5
{ An attempt to create chaos on the board. Despite the sharp nature of the variations we're about to examine, this line has been worked out to a clear White advantage in correspondence chess. Nevertheless, precise knowledge of the following lines is necessary. }
8. Ndb5 { Threatening Nxc7 and exd5. } 8... Bb4
{ is Black's only logical follow-up to 7...d5. Black pins the c3 knight and wants to continue with ...d4 and ...Nxe4. }
9. O-O-O
{ is an important move, stopping ...d4 and renewing the threat of Nxc7. } 9...
c6 10. Nc7
{ It's finally time to jump into c7, going after Black's rook on a8. } 10...
Nxe4 11. Qd4 Nxc3
{ is not nearly as common as  11...Bxc3  , but has also occurred in practice. It fails to give Black sufficient counterplay. }
12. bxc3 Ba3+ 13. Kb1
{ Objectively White is much better here. Black does have some practical chances due to the exposed nature of White's king, but it's insufficient and White just needs to take a modicum of care to convert his advantage.   A sample continuation is  13...Be6  14.Nxa8  Qa5  15.Bd2  Na6  16.c4  Bb4  Now  17.Bxb4!  Nxb4  combined with  18.a3  puts an end to Black's desperate try for counterplay following  18...Qxa3  19.Qa1  forces the queens of the board.  19...Qxa1+  20.Kxa1  Rxa8  21.c3  Na6  22.cxd5  Bxd5  23.Bxa6  bxa6  24.f3+−  with Rd4 on the agenda is a technically winning ending. }
