1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 exd4
{ Clarifying the tension in the center is by far Black's main move. } 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7
{ is known as the Antonishin variation and is Black's most popular continuation. }
6. Bf4
{ This has been established as White's best setup in correspondence chess. The idea is both simple and aggressive: White intends Qd2 followed by O-O-O. }
6... O-O 7. Qd2 d5
{ An attempt to create chaos on the board. Despite the sharp nature of the variations we're about to examine, this line has been worked out to a clear White advantage in correspondence chess. Nevertheless, precise knowledge of the following lines is necessary. }
8. Ndb5 { Threatening Nxc7 and exd5. } 8... Bb4
{ is Black's only logical follow-up to 7...d5. Black pins the c3 knight and wants to continue with ...d4 and ...Nxe4. }
9. O-O-O
{ is an important move, stopping ...d4 and renewing the threat of Nxc7. } 9...
c6 10. Nc7
{ It's finally time to jump into c7, going after Black's rook on a8. } 10...
Nxe4 11. Qd4 Bxc3 { is Black's best shot at creating counterplay. } 12. bxc3
Qe7
{ with the idea Qa3 to attack White's king. However, with only a queen and knight, Black's attack will easily be parried. }
13. c4 { White clears the way for Qb2, anticipating ...Qa3+. } 13... Qa3+ 14.
Qb2 Qa5
{ Exchanging the queens with  14...Qxb2  leads to a losing endgame after  15.Kxb2  Nxf2  16.Be2  Nxh1  17.Rxh1+−  White will capture the rook on a8 on the next turn and end up with an extra piece. }
15. cxd5 Nxf2 16. Be2
{ Simply developing and covering the rook on h1. We're not in a hurry to capture the rook on a8 as it's not going anywhere. Importantly, White will be able to extricate his knight from a8 as the c7 square is recovered. As such, we'll recoup the sacrificed material with interest.  Finally, note that all of White's pieces are now in the game. Conversely, most of Black's pieces are still on the back rank. All in all, White is clearly for choice.   I don't see much need in remembering any more moves but I've covered Black's two best moves,  16...Na6  and  16...Nxh1  , in the following two alternative lines. This gives you the option of training them if you see fit. }
