1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7 6. Bf4 O-O 7. Qd2 d5 8.
Ndb5 Bb4 9. O-O-O c6 10. Nc7 Nxe4 11. Qd4 Bxc3 12. bxc3 Qe7 13. c4 Qa3+ 14. Qb2
Qa5 15. cxd5 Nxf2 16. Be2 { Black can capture the rook on h1 right away with }
16... Nxh1 17. Rxh1 Bf5 18. Nxa8
{ White has an extra piece for only two pawns which means Black does not have anywhere near enough compensation. }
18... Re8
{ Worse is  18...Qxd5  19.Re1  White is now threatening g2-g4 and Nc7.  19...Qxg2  20.Nc7  Nd7  21.Bg3+−  White has an extra piece and can continue with Bf1 or Qxb7, with a decisive advantage. }
19. Bf3 { Moving the bishop to safety. } 19... Na6 20. Bd2
{ Attacking Black's queen and stopping ...Nb4. } 20... Qa4 21. Qb3 Qd4 22. Re1
{ Takes control over the key e-file. } 22... Rxa8
{ Black has finally recouped his piece but his entire queenside is about to collapse. }
23. Qxb7 Rd8 24. Qb2 { Covers the a1 square, stopping ...Qa1+. } 24... Qxb2+
25. Kxb2 cxd5 26. Re7 Be4 27. Rxa7
{ White's bishop pair and outside passed a-pawn easily decided the game in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@41@@EndBracket@@ Triay Moll, L @@StartBracket@@2360@@EndBracket@@ - Keskowski, T @@StartBracket@@2394@@EndBracket@@ corr ICCF 2017. }
