[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7 6. Bf4 O-O 7. Qd2 d5 8.
Ndb5 Bb4 9. O-O-O c6 10. Nc7 Nxe4 11. Qd4 Bxc3 12. bxc3 Qe7 13. c4 Qa3+ 14. Qb2
Qa5 15. cxd5 Nxf2 16. Be2 Na6 17. Nxa8 Nxh1
{ 17...Nb4?  is a blunder.  18.Bd2  Pinning and winning!  18...Nxa2+  19.Kb1+−  simply picks up Black's knight on a2. }
18. Rxh1 Nb4
{ 18...Re8  is strongly met by  19.Bd2  hitting Black's queen.  19...Qxd5  20.Re1  White is now threatening Bxa6.  20...b6  21.Qc3+−  Bf3 is coming next with a clear advantage. White is after all a piece up. }
19. Bc4 { Covering the a2 pawn. } 19... Qc5 20. a3
{ It's now time to get rid of Black's annoying knight. } 20... Nxc2
{ A nice tactic, with the idea of eliminating all of White's queenside pawns.   Worse is  20...Nxd5  21.Bxd5  cxd5  22.Nc7+−  White is a piece up and thus clearly better. }
21. Qxc2 Qxa3+ 22. Kd2
{ White is currently two pieces up so Black must act swiftly. } 22... cxd5 23.
Qc3 { Forcing the queens of the board. } 23... Qxc3+
{ 23...Qe7?  24.Bd3+−  Nc7 is coming next. White has two extra minor pieces and is thus completely winning. }
24. Kxc3 dxc4 25. Nc7
{ Kxc4 and Ra1 are on the agenda. White swiftly converted the extra piece in the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Verhaeren, G @@StartBracket@@2357@@EndBracket@@-Boreux, P @@StartBracket@@2209@@EndBracket@@ corr ICCF 2017. }
