1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 exd4
{ Clarifying the tension in the center is by far Black's main move. } 4. Nxd4
Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7
{ is known as the Antonishin variation and is Black's most popular continuation. }
6. Bf4
{ This has been established as White's best setup in correspondence chess. The idea is both simple and aggressive: White intends Qd2 followed by O-O-O. }
6... O-O 7. Qd2 d5
{ An attempt to create chaos on the board. Despite the sharp nature of the variations we're about to examine, this line has been worked out to a clear White advantage in correspondence chess. Nevertheless, precise knowledge of the following lines is necessary. }
8. Ndb5 { is a key move, threatening Nxc7 and exd5. } 8... c6
{ White naturally jumps in with } 9. Nc7 d4 { is the only way to continue. }
10. Nxa8 dxc3 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. bxc3
{ is a winning endgame for White. The main point is that Black is unable to trap our knight on a8 as the following sample continuations illustrate:   12...Nbd7  is well met by  13.f3  Nf8  14.Rb1  b5  15.Nc7  when the knight successfully escapes.   12...Nxe4  is a better try. White gets a decisive advantage after  13.Bd3  Bd6   13...Nc5  doesn't change much. Following  14.Bxb8  Nxd3  15.cxd3  Bf5  16.Bxa7  Rxa8  17.Bb6  Bxd3  18.a4  a5 is coming next when White is simply up an exchange.  14.Bxd6  Nxd6  15.O-O-O  Kf8  16.Be2  Rd7  17.Rd4!  White's h1 rook is on the way to d1 after which the knight on c7 will once again escape. }
