1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ characterizes the Petroff defense. This opening, which is also known as the Russian defense, has a reputation for being rock-solid and has been the choice of several top-GMs such as Anand, Karpov, Kramnik, and Caruana in multiple World-Championship matches and Candidates tournaments. }
3. Nxe5
{ The Classical variation is White's most ambitious option and my recommendation. }
3... Qe7
{ makes little sense as Black could simply recoup the e4 pawn with 3...d6. } 4.
d4 { 4.Nf3  also leads to an advantage but the text is stronger. } 4... d6 5.
Nf3 Nxe4 6. Be2
{ Blocking the e-file and clearing the way for O-O followed by Re1. Black may control the e-file for now, but this is only temporary. }
6... g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1
{ when Black has a lot of problems along the e-file. For example } 8... O-O 9.
Bc4
{ wins the knight.   For example  9...Bf5  is met by  10.Nbd2  Re8  11.Bd5  Qd7  12.Bxe4+−  wins the knight. This variation can be trained in the followingtactical puzzle. }
