[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ characterizes the Petroff defense. This opening, which is also known as the Russian defense, has a reputation for being rock-solid and has been the choice of several top-GMs such as Anand, Karpov, Kramnik, and Caruana in multiple World-Championship matches and Candidates tournaments. }
3. Nxe5
{ The Classical variation is White's most ambitious option and my recommendation. }
3... Qe7
{ makes little sense as Black could simply recoup the e4 pawn with 3...d6. } 4.
d4 { 4.Nf3  also leads to an advantage but the text is stronger. } 4... d6 5.
Nf3 Qxe4+ { is check but that's about it. } 6. Be2 Bf5 7. Na3
{ Covers the c2 pawn. The knight might look offside on a3 but it can jump to b5 later on, hitting the vulnerable c7 pawn. }
7... Qe6 8. Nh4 { Hitting the f5 bishop. } 8... Be4 9. Nb5
{ Forces Black's queen to move once again. The knight will then head to c3 to target Black's e4 bishop. }
9... Qd7 10. Nc3 d5 11. O-O Nc6 12. Nxe4 { picks up the bishop pair. } 12...
Nxe4
{ 12...dxe4  can be met with  13.c3  reinforcing the d4 pawn. After  13...O-O-O  14.f3±  opens up the position for White's bishops with a clear advantage. }
13. Bg4 Qd8 14. Nf5
{ gives White a clear advantage. We are almost fully mobilized while Black's king is still on e8! }
