[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 Nc6
{ is the infamous Stafford gambit, which was popularized by IM Eric Rosen and other well-known streamers.  @@StartBlockQuote@@The Stafford Gambit is the trappiest opening in chess. - IM Eric Rosen@@EndBlockQuote@@Why did it become so popular? Here are some of the frequent traps White has fallen into.   4.Nxc6  dxc6  5.e5  Ne4  6.d3??  is natural but already losing to  6...Bc5  7.dxe4  when  7...Bxf2  wins White's queen.  8.Kxf2  Qxd1−+  while  8.Ke2  still loses to  8...Bg4−+   Another common trick is  4.Nxc6  dxc6  5.d3  Bc5  Here the natural  6.Bg5??  runs into  6...Nxe4!  7.Bxd8  7...Bxf2  is mate and has occurred well over 700 times on Lichess! Note  7.Qe2  doesn't lose outright but Black is still winning after  7...Qxg5  8.Qxe4  Kd8!  clearing the way for ...Re8!  9.Be2  Qc1  10.Bd1  Re8−+   Yet another one is  4.Nxc6  dxc6  5.Nc3  Bc5  6.Bc4?  is another natural move that runs into trouble on f2 after  6...Ng4  when  7.O-O?  loses to  7...Qh4  8.h3  Nxf2  crashing through. For example  9.Qf3  Nxh3  10.Kh1  Nf2  11.Kg1  Qh1  is mate! }
4. Nxc6 dxc6
{ This course includes what I believe are the two strongest and easiest to learn/most practical ways to refute this gambit. }
5. e5
{ is mymain recommendation.   5.d3  is another excellent option, which is given in a set of alternative lines startinghere. }
