1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ characterizes the Petroff defense. This opening, which is also known as the Russian defense, has a reputation for being rock-solid and has been the choice of several top-GMs such as Anand, Karpov, Kramnik, and Caruana in multiple World-Championship matches and Candidates tournaments. }
3. Nxe5
{ The Classical variation is White's most ambitious option and my recommendation. }
3... Nc6
{ is the infamous Stafford gambit, which was popularized by IM Eric Rosen and other well-known streamers.  @@StartBlockQuote@@The Stafford Gambit is the trappiest opening in chess. - IM Eric Rosen@@EndBlockQuote@@Why did it become so popular? Here are some of the frequent traps White has fallen into.   4.Nxc6  dxc6  5.e5  Ne4  6.d3??  is natural but already losing to  6...Bc5  7.dxe4  when  7...Bxf2  wins White's queen.  8.Kxf2  Qxd1−+  while  8.Ke2  still loses to  8...Bg4−+   Another common trick is  4.Nxc6  dxc6  5.d3  Bc5  Here the natural  6.Bg5??  runs into  6...Nxe4!  7.Bxd8  7...Bxf2  is mate and has occurred well over 700 times on Lichess! Note  7.Qe2  doesn't lose outright but Black is still winning after  7...Qxg5  8.Qxe4  Kd8!  clearing the way for ...Re8!  9.Be2  Qc1  10.Bd1  Re8−+   Yet another one is  4.Nxc6  dxc6  5.Nc3  Bc5  6.Bc4?  is another natural move that runs into trouble on f2 after  6...Ng4  when  7.O-O?  loses to  7...Qh4  8.h3  Nxf2  crashing through. For example  9.Qf3  Nxh3  10.Kh1  Nf2  11.Kg1  Qh1  is mate!  We'll avoid all the tricks and easily put it out of business in three trainable lines. The variation I'm about to suggest is one of the strongest and easiest to learn. }
4. Nxc6 bxc6
{ is not the way to go as Black's light-squared bishop is blocked in. } 5. Nc3
d5
{ is the only sensible continuation.   Worse is  5...Bb4  as after  6.e5  Qe7  7.Qe2  Nd5  8.Nxd5  cxd5  9.c3  Ba5  10.d4±  White is a clean pawn up and is threatening to pick up another one with Qb5. }
6. e5 Nd7 7. d4
{ White is a pawn up and has complete control of the center. The only line remotely worth knowing is }
7... c5 { where Black sacrifices the d5 pawn hoping that after } 8. Nxd5 cxd4
9. Qxd4 Nb6
{ he can exploit the pin along the d-file. However, White is winning with the tactical sequence }
10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Bg5
{ distracting Black's queen from the defense of the c7 pawn. } 11... Qxg5 12.
Nxc7+ Kd8 13. Nxa8
{ is lights out. The knight on a8 is untouchable as Qxd7# would then follow. }
