{ is almost invariable played. Black wants to play ...Ng4 to target the f2 pawn. }
6. Be2 { Black can also try to prepare ...Ng4 with } 6... h5
{ but this is too slow, giving White enough time to expand in the center with }
7. c3 { followed by d2-d4, which will neutralize Black's bishop. } 7... Ng4 8.
d4 Bb6 9. h3 { Pushes back Black's knight. } 9... Nf6 10. Bg5
{ gives White a decisive advantage. We are a pawn up, have full control over the center, and Black's pawn on h5 will be a target later on.   A sample continuation is  10...Qd7  11.Nd2  c5  12.d5  c6  13.c4  cxd5  14.cxd5!+-  with an overwhelming position. }
