1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ characterizes the Petroff defense. This opening, which is also known as the Russian defense, has a reputation for being rock-solid and has been the choice of several top-GMs such as Anand, Karpov, Kramnik, and Caruana in multiple World-Championship matches and Candidates tournaments. }
3. Nxe5
{ The Classical variation is White's most ambitious option and my recommendation. }
3... Nxe4 { is very dubious as Black will be in trouble along the e-file. } 4.
Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4
{ Reinforces the knight on e5 and opens up the dark-squared bishop. Black can regain the pawn with accurate play but will never come close to equalizing. }
6... Nc6 7. Bb5 Bd7 8. Bg5
{ is a fantastic tactical shot, lewering Black's queen away from the e-file. }
8... f6 9. Nc3
{ is a great move - the knight will land into d5 with decisive effect. Two of our pieces are hanging, but as the legendary attacker Mikhail Tal once remarked 'he can only take one at a time!' }
9... dxe5
{ 9...fxg5?  is even worse as  10.Nd5  Qd8  11.Nxc6++-  wins Black's queen. }
10. Nd5
{ Black has restored material equality but the pawn on c7 will be his undoing. }
10... Qd6 11. dxe5 Qxe5 12. Nxc7+ Kd8 13. Bxc6
{ picks up the knight while protecting the queen. } 13... Qxe4+
{ 13...Qxc7  is not an improvement. After  14.Bxd7  Qxd7  15.Bf4+-  is decisive. We're already a pawn up and Black's king is in no man's land.   13...Bxc6??  blunders the queen to  14.Qxe5+-  as the f6 pawn is pinned. }
14. Bxe4 Kxc7 15. Bf4+ Kb6 16. O-O-O
{ We're a pawn up, ahead in development and have more active pieces. You get the picture, White has a decisive advantage. }
