[White "3. Petroff | 3rd move options [inc. Stafford Gambit]"]
[Black "3...Nxe4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ characterizes the Petroff defense. This opening, which is also known as the Russian defense, has a reputation for being rock-solid and has been the choice of several top-GMs such as Anand, Karpov, Kramnik, and Caruana in multiple World-Championship matches and Candidates tournaments. }
3. Nxe5
{ The Classical variation is White's most ambitious option and my recommendation. }
3... Nxe4 { is very dubious as Black will be in trouble along the e-file. } 4.
Qe2 Qe7 5. Qxe4 d6 6. d4
{ Reinforces the knight on e5 and opens up the dark-squared bishop. Black can regain the pawn with accurate play but will never come close to equalizing. }
6... dxe5 7. dxe5 Nc6 8. Nc3
{ is the simplest route towards a big advantage. We give back the extra pawn in exchange for piece activity. }
8... Qxe5 9. Qxe5+ Nxe5 10. Nb5
{ Black has no good way of covering the c7 pawn. } 10... Bb4+
{ is arguably Black's best choice but it fails to equalize.   10...Kd8  leaves the king very exposed. After  11.Bf4  f6  12.O-O-O+±  White is clearly for choice.   10...Bd6  11.Nxd6+  cxd6  12.Be3±  is much better for White. The d6 pawn is about to be targeted with O-O-O, not to mention we have the two bishops. }
11. Bd2 Bxd2+ 12. Kxd2 Kd8
{ If Black could play both ...a6 and ...Kd8 at once, he would be fine. However, that's illegal and White's extra activity gives us an advantage. Following... }
13. Re1 f6
{ Alternatively  13...Nc6  runs into  14.Bc4  14...f6  15.Kc1±  when Black's king on d8 is once again exposed.   13...Ng6  can be met with  14.h4±  with the idea h5 and a clear advantage.   Finally  13...Nd7  is strongly met by  14.h4  a6  15.Nc3  Re8  16.Bc4  Ne5  17.Bb3±  Next up is f4 with a clear advantage. }
14. f4 Ng6 15. g3 a6 16. Nd4
{ We're about to complete development with Bg2 while Black is still several moves away from doing the same. We can then expand on the kingside with h4-h5 with a long-lasting advantage. }
