1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 Be7
{ 5...Qe7  can simply be met with  6.Be2  which transposes to the3...Qe7 #1 variation in chapter  3. }
6. Bd3 Ng5
{ Seeking to exchange the knights is the only option with independent value, but not a good one.   6...Nf6  or  6...d5  will transpose to one of the mainlines at Black's disposal, which are covered in chapters5-7. }
7. Nxg5 Bxg5 8. Qe2+
{ forces Black's bishop back, making the best of a bad situation. } 8... Be7
{ 8...Be6  isn't much of an improvement. After  9.f4  Bh4  10.g3  Be7  11.O-O±  Black is in big trouble with f5 and Re1 in the cards.   8...Qe7??  blunders a piece to  9.Bxg5+- }
9. O-O O-O 10. Qe4
{ forces Black to weaken his kingside, giving White a big edge. } 10... g6 11.
Nc3
{ with ideas of Re1 and Nd5. Black's pieces are very passive and his king is already weakened, which is obviously not a good combination.   A sample continuation is  11.Nc3  Re8  12.Nd5  Bf8  is the move Black would like to play, fighting for the e-file but it loses to  13.Qxe8!  Qxe8  14.Nf6+  Kh8  15.Nxe8+-  White is up a full rook. }
