1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 Bg4 { only has independent value if after } 6. Bd3
{ Black goes for the weakening } 6... f5
{ is a very dubious attempt of entrenching the knight on e4.   The more logical  6...d5  is covered via the 5...d5 6...Bg4 move order inchapter 5.   6...Nf6  is covered via the5...Nf6 6. Bd3 Bg4 move order. }
7. c3 { is very precise, clearing the way for Qb3. } 7... Nd7 8. Qb3
{ threatens to invade with Qe6+, exploiting the drawback of the 6... f5 move which weakened the e6 square. }
8... Qe7 9. O-O
{ Gets the king off the e-file avoiding any discoveries.   Watch out! The greedy  9.Qxb7??  blunders the queen to  9...Nec5−+ }
9... O-O-O
{ is a logical move, developing the queenside while covering the b7 pawn.   Worse is  9...Bxf3  which only helps us open the e-file and get rid of Black's knight with  10.gxf3  Ng5  11.Qxb7  Rb8  12.Qd5+-  White is up a pawn, the one on f5 is hanging, and Black has no good way of completing development. }
10. Ne1 { wins material. The immediate threat is a fork with f3. } 10... Bh5
11. f3 Ng5 12. Bxf5
{ nets White a pawn. Black has no compensation for the material deficit. } *

