{ 6...d5  transposes to one of the mainlines at Black's disposal. Seechapter 5 for the details. }
7. h3 O-O 8. O-O Re8
{ Black's rook surely belongs on e8 so Black should start with this move.   8...Nc6  is not where the knight belongs since  9.c3±  completely restricts it. }
9. c4 Nbd7
{ is the right square for the knight, intending to scoot it over to the kingside to protect Black's king and possibly pressure the d4 pawn with ...Nf8-e6.   9...Nc6  misplaces the knight. After  10.Nc3  d5  11.c5±  Black has less space on the queenside and no active plan. }
10. Nc3 Nf8 11. Re1 { Our typical move, improving the placement of the rook. }
11... Ng6
{ 11...Ne6  runs into  12.d5±  forcing the knight back.   11...c6  is similarly met by  12.d5±  which gave White a big space advantage in the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@22@@EndBracket@@ Kovalev,A @@StartBracket@@2501@@EndBracket@@ -Laurusas,T @@StartBracket@@2433@@EndBracket@@ Lithuania 2017. }
12. Qb3
{ is an active square for the queen, keeping tabs on the b7 pawn and solidifying White's control over the d5 square. }
12... c6 13. Bg5
{ is clearly better for White, who has more space and superior central control. Control over the e-file can be increased by doubling up with Re2 and Rae1. }
