1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Bg4
{ Prioritizing development of the queenside pieces cannot be recommended. } 7.
h3 { Immediately puts the question to the bishop. } 7... Bf5
{ is more solid than  7...Bh5  but still fails to equalize. If Black wanted to put his bishop here, he should have done so in one go on move  6. }
8. O-O Be7 9. c4
{ with the usual theme of undermining Black's knight on e4.   9.Re1  is a good alternative. }
9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 O-O 11. Nc3
{ Challenging Black's loose knight on e4, and attempting to define the pawn structure. }
11... Nxc3
{ Alternatively  11...Nd6  can be met with  12.Bb3  Nc6  13.Re1±  followed by Bf4-e5 with a big edge. }
12. bxc3
{ is an exchange we welcome, reinforcing the d4 pawn and opening up the b-file for our rook. }
12... Nc6 13. Re1
{ White is slightly better here. Our plan is to complete development with Bf4 and potentially expand on the queenside with a4-a5. }
