1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Nf6
{ Black spends a full tempo retreating the knight to avoid having to reinforce it. Such an approach is rather cooperative and gives White a slight advantage in all the variations. Black is banking on the fact that the symmetric pawn structure will keep White's activity and advantage within controllable bounds. }
7. O-O Be7 8. Re1
{ is a useful move and retains maximum flexibility. The rook surely belongs on e1, so White does best in playing it first before touching the queenside. Not committing the queenside pieces immediately allows us to adapt to Black's setup. }
8... Bg4 { is premature for a very concrete reason. } 9. h3 Bh5
{ 9...Bxf3  surrenders the bishop pair and gives White a clear advantage.  10.Qxf3± }
10. Nc3 O-O 11. g4
{ Black is now in trouble as g5 is coming next. The point is that if Black's knight moves back, then the d5 pawn will hang as Black's queen is overloaded defending the bishop on e7 along with the d5 pawn. }
11... Bg6 12. g5 Nh5
{ While  13.Nxd5  works, Black has some compensation after  13...Qxd5  14.Rxe7  Nc6  Even stronger is }
13. Be2
{ threatens to win a piece with Ne5/h2. Black has no good solution.   For example  13...Nc6  14.Nh2  Nb4  15.Bxh5  Bxh5  16.Qxh5  Nxc2  17.Bf4  Nxa1  18.Rxa1±  when White's two knights are stronger than Black's rook and pawn. }
