1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Nd6
{ is Black's 7th most popular move. Similar to 6...Nf6, Black spends a full tempo retreating the knight to safety. From d6, the knight controls the c4-square, effectively stopping White from challenging the d-pawn with c2-c4, and supports ...Bf5 in some variations. The drawback is the knight takes away the best square for Black's bishop on f8. }
7. O-O Be7 8. c3
{ is only White's 5th most popular move but one of the top choices of the neural network engines. It reinforces the d4 pawn and opens up the possibility of Qb3. }
8... O-O
{ Black has no time for   8...Bf5?!  as  9.Bxf5  Nxf5  10.Qb3  forces Black to severely weaken his queenside with  10...b6  11.Re1±  followed by c4 will open up the position in White's favor. }
9. Re1 Nd7
{ is the best square for Black's knight. A typical maneuver in this structure is ...Re8 followed by ... Nf8-g6/e6. }
10. Bf4
{ is the best square for the bishop. The plan is to complete development with Nbd2 and Qb3. }
10... Re8 11. Nbd2 Nf8 12. Qb3 { Develops the queen with tempo. } 12... c6 13.
h3
{ is a useful move, creating a square for the bishop on h2 in case of ...Ne6/g6. }
13... Ne6 14. Bh2 g6
{ Black's plan is to swap off the light-squared bishops with ...Ng7 followed by ...Bf5. If he were able to achieve that, he'd have fully equalized. The problem however is that White can immediately strike with }
15. c4 { undermining Black's d-pawn. } 15... Ng7
{ is a novelty and not a particularly good one as it allows } 16. c5
{ forcing Black's knight to f5 - a square it didn't want to go to  (as ...Bf5 was Black's plan)  . }
16... Ndf5 17. a4
{ with good play. White can choose to gain further space on the queenside with a5 or instead double on the e-file with Re2 followed by Rae1. In both cases, the extra space on the queenside and superiorly placed minor pieces give White a sizeable advantage. Black's knights, on the other hand, are stepping on each other's toes. }
