[Black "6...Bf5 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Bf5
{ is connected with the idea of exchanging off the light-squared bishops with ...Nd6 later on. }
7. O-O Be7 8. Re1 O-O
{ is the only independent option.   8...Nc6  9.Nbd2  is covered in chapter 7 via the6... Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nbd2 move order. }
9. Nbd2
{ Quickly undermining Black's e4 knight is my preference here.   9.c4  is also possible but White has been unable to put any pressure on Black's position.  9...Nc6  10.cxd5  Qxd5  11.Nc3  Nxc3  12.bxc3  Bxd3  13.Qxd3  Rae8  14.Bf4  Bd6  15.c4  Qh5  16.Bxd6  cxd6  17.Qa3  Qa5  18.Qxd6  Rxe1+  19.Rxe1=  All the OTB games that reached this position were effortlessly drawn. A few relatively recent examples are 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2761@@EndBracket@@-Wei,Y @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ Abidjan 2019, ½-½ @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2767@@EndBracket@@ -Wei,Y @@StartBracket@@2743@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2018 and ½-½ @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Naiditsch,A @@StartBracket@@2695@@EndBracket@@-Li,C @@StartBracket@@2691@@EndBracket@@ China 2019. }
9... Nd6
{ Following through with Black's original idea of trading the light-squared bishops.   9...Nxd2?!  hands over the bishop pair for no reason. After  10.Bxf5  Nxf3+  11.Qxf3±  White is threatening Qh3 and is clearly for choice. }
10. Nf1
{ Nb1-d2-f1 is a typical maneuver in this structure. The knight can later head to g3, hitting the f5 bishop, or e3 to pressure the d5 pawn depending on how Black proceeds. }
10... Bxd3
{ 10...Nd7  is another possible move order.  11.Bf4  Bxd3  12.Qxd3  Re8  13.Qb3+=  transposes   10...c6  11.Bf4  Bxd3  12.Qxd3  also transposes to the text. }
11. Qxd3
{ Let's take stock. The pawn structure is symmetrical but White's pieces are better placed, which gives us a slight advantage.  The dark-squared bishop is coming to f4, which will be more active than Black's bishop on e7. Our queen is headed to b3 to pressure the d5 and b7 pawns and is more active than Black's queen.  Finally, the f1 knight is headed to e3 while Black's b8 knight still occupies the starting square. }
11... Nd7 12. Bf4
{ is typically the best square for the bishop, where it's most active. } 12...
Re8 13. Qb3 { The only way to cover both pawns is } 13... Nb6 14. a4
{ is a typical move, gaining space on the queenside and intending to push back Black's pieces with a5. White can also consider expanding on the other side of the board with h4 later on. While Black is quite solid, he lacks an active plan.   White had slightly better chances, going on to win in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Dominguez Perez,L @@StartBracket@@2758@@EndBracket@@-Duda,J @@StartBracket@@2743@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021. This game is analyzed in themodel games chapter. }
