1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/ Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Bf5
{ is connected with the idea of exchanging off the light-squared bishops with ... Nd6 later on. }
7. O-O Be7 8. Re1 O-O
{ is the only independent option.   8...Nc6  9.Nbd2  transposes to 6... Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nbd2, which is covered in chapter 7. }
9. Nbd2
{ Quickly undermining Black's e4 knight is my preference here.   9.c4  is also possible but White has been unable to put any pressure.  9...Nc6  10.cxd5  Qxd5  11.Nc3  Nxc3  12.bxc3  Bxd3  13.Qxd3  Rae8  14.Bf4  Bd6  15.c4  Qh5  16.Bxd6  cxd6  17.Qa3  Qa5  18.Qxd6  Rxe1+  19.Rxe1=  All the OTB games that reached this position were effortlessly drawn. A few relatively recent examples are 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2761@@EndBracket@@-Wei,Y @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ Abidjan 2019, ½-½  @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2767@@EndBracket@@ -Wei,Y @@StartBracket@@2743@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2018 and ½-½ @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Naiditsch,A @@StartBracket@@2695@@EndBracket@@-Li,C @@StartBracket@@2691@@EndBracket@@ China 2019. }
9... Nd6
{ 9...Nxd2?!  hands over the bishop pair for no reason. After  10.Bxf5  Nxf3+  11.Qxf3±  White is threatening Qh3 and clearly for choice. }
10. Nf1 Bxd3 11. Qxd3
{ Let's take stock. The pawn structure is symmetrical but White's pieces are better placed. Coming up is Bf4, Qb3, and Ne3 to pressure the d5 and b7 pawns. }
11... c6
{ Reinforcing the d5 pawn is Black's best move and has been played by several strong GMs such as Polish superstar GM Jan-Krzysztof Duda as well as Chinese super-GM Yu Yangyi to name a few. }
12. Bf4 Nd7
{ was only played a handful of times and is not very accurate because of } 13.
Qb3
{ creating immediate problems. White is threatening to pick up the b7 pawn with Bxd6 followed by Qxb7. }
13... Nb6 { Covers the pawn but is strongly met by } 14. a4
{ intending to push ahead with a5. } 14... Nbc4
{ This position occurred in the top-level game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Esipenko,A @@StartBracket@@2677@@EndBracket@@-Duda,J @@StartBracket@@2743@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2021. The novel }
15. Ng3
{ is much more challenging than   15.Ne5  Nxe5  16.dxe5  Ne4=  when Duda fully equalized and went on to draw the game. }
15... Qd7
{ Completing development and covering the  b7  pawn. This is both more natural and objectively stronger than  15...Re8  which is strongly met by  16.Qc3  clearing the way for b2-b3.  16...a5  is connected with the idea of meeting b3 with ...Ne4 followed by ...Bb4 with excellent counterplay. However, we can stop all these shenanigans with  17.Rab1  which vacates the a1 square for the Queen in response to ...Bb4. And no, I didn't come up with such a deep move, Leela and Stockfish of course did!  Bf8  18.b3+=  knocks back Black's knight and gives White a slight advantage. We're ready to spring forward with Ne5 on the next turn. }
16. c3 Rfe8
{ Black covers the e7 bishop and is now threatening to push back our bishop with ...Qg4. }
17. h3 f6 18. Qc2
{ followed by b3 will boot Black's knight. An interesting maneuver Leela points out is to reroute the f3 knight with Nh2-g4-e3 to support the c4 break.   White is slightly better although Black should be able to maintain the balance with precise play. }
