1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/ Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Bf5
{ is connected with the idea of exchanging off the light-squared bishops with ... Nd6 later on. }
7. O-O Be7 8. Re1 O-O
{ is the only independent option.   8...Nc6  9.Nbd2  transposes to 6... Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nbd2, which is covered in chapter 7. }
9. Nbd2
{ Quickly undermining Black's e4 knight is my preference here.   9.c4  is also possible but White has been unable to put any pressure.  9...Nc6  10.cxd5  Qxd5  11.Nc3  Nxc3  12.bxc3  Bxd3  13.Qxd3  Rae8  14.Bf4  Bd6  15.c4  Qh5  16.Bxd6  cxd6  17.Qa3  Qa5  18.Qxd6  Rxe1+  19.Rxe1=  All the OTB games that reached this position were effortlessly drawn. A few relatively recent examples are 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2761@@EndBracket@@-Wei,Y @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ Abidjan 2019, ½-½  @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2767@@EndBracket@@ -Wei,Y @@StartBracket@@2743@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2018 and ½-½ @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Naiditsch,A @@StartBracket@@2695@@EndBracket@@-Li,C @@StartBracket@@2691@@EndBracket@@ China 2019. }
9... Nd6
{ 9...Nxd2?!  hands over the bishop pair for no reason. After  10.Bxf5  Nxf3+  11.Qxf3±  White is threatening Qh3 and clearly for choice. }
10. Nf1 Bxd3 11. Qxd3
{ Let's take stock. The pawn structure is symmetrical but White's pieces are better placed. Coming up is Bf4, Qb3, and Ne3 to pressure the d5 and b7 pawns. }
11... c6
{ Reinforcing the d5 pawn is Black's best move and has been played by several strong GMs such as Polish superstar GM Jan-Krzysztof Duda as well as Chinese super-GM Yu Yangyi to name a few. }
12. Bf4 Na6 { planning to reroute the knight to e6 is a better option. } 13. h4
{ was first played by Nepomniatchi against Wang Hao, scoring a full point in the 2020 Candidates tournament. Nepo's immediate idea is to support Ng5, noting that the h-pawn can later be pushed to weaken Black's kingside. }
13... Nc7 14. Ng5
{ The attack on the h7 pawn forces a concession.   14.Ne3  N  with the idea Bxd6 followed by Nf5 fails to give White anything tangible.  14...Ne6  15.Bxd6  Bxd6  16.g3  Re8  17.Re2  h5  18.Rae1=  18...Qd7  19.Nf5  White got his knight to f5 but it's short-lived.  19...g6  20.Nxd6  Qxd6=  and Black will eventually equalize by swapping rooks on the e-file. }
14... Bxg5
{ avoids weakening the kingside but confines Black to passivity. All of Black's pawns are on light-squares so giving up the dark-squared bishop is a big concession. }
15. Bxg5 { forces Black to weaken the kingside with } 15... f6
{ 15...Qd7?  allows White to invade with  16.Re7±  causing Black lots of problems. }
16. Bf4 Qd7 { Here I'd like to recommend the novel } 17. Ne3
{ We're planning to swap off Black's knight and then jump in with Nf5.   This is more accurate than  17.Ng3  which occurred in the game 1-0  (43)  Nepomniachtchi,I  (2774)  -Wang,H  (2762)  Ekaterinburg 2020. The difference will be explained in a note to Black's next move. }
17... Rae8
{ The reason 17. Ne3 is more accurate than Nepo's 17. Ng3 is that it enables White to meet  17...g6  with  18.h5  f5  19.hxg6  hxg6  and now White can play  20.Ng4!  This move is only possible when White places his knight on e3 all the way back on move 17. This is the key difference! }
18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. Nf5
{ The knight lands on its desired outpost, controlling several key squares and exerting strong pressure on Black's kingside. }
19... Qd7 20. Qh3
{ gave White the upper hand in the game 1-0  (43)  Nepomniachtchi,I  (2774)  -Wang,H  (2762)  Ekaterinburg 2020. While the immediate threat is Nh6+, White is also ready to expand on the kingside with h4-h5. Nepo placed Wang Hao under sustained pressure for several moves, which caused him to eventually crack. This game is annotated in themodel games chapter. }
