{ is the only independent option.   8...Nc6  9.Nbd2  transposes to 6... Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. Nbd2, which is covered in chapter 7. }
9. Nbd2
{ Quickly undermining Black's e4 knight is my preference here.   9.c4  is also possible but White has been unable to put any pressure.  9...Nc6  10.cxd5  Qxd5  11.Nc3  Nxc3  12.bxc3  Bxd3  13.Qxd3  Rae8  14.Bf4  Bd6  15.c4  Qh5  16.Bxd6  cxd6  17.Qa3  Qa5  18.Qxd6  Rxe1+  19.Rxe1=  All the OTB games that reached this position were effortlessly drawn. A few relatively recent examples are 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2761@@EndBracket@@-Wei,Y @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ Abidjan 2019, ½-½  @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2767@@EndBracket@@ -Wei,Y @@StartBracket@@2743@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2018 and ½-½ @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Naiditsch,A @@StartBracket@@2695@@EndBracket@@-Li,C @@StartBracket@@2691@@EndBracket@@ China 2019. }
9... Nd6
{ 9...Nxd2?!  hands over the bishop pair for no reason. After  10.Bxf5  Nxf3+  11.Qxf3±  White is threatening Qh3 and clearly for choice. }
10. Nf1 Bxd3 11. Qxd3
{ Let's take stock. The pawn structure is symmetrical but White's pieces are better placed. Coming up is Bf4, Qb3, and Ne3 to pressure the d5 and b7 pawns. }
11... c6
{ Reinforcing the d5 pawn is Black's best move and has been played by several strong GMs such as Polish superstar GM Jan-Krzysztof Duda as well as Chinese super-GM Yu Yangyi to name a few. }
12. Bf4 Na6 { planning to reroute the knight to e6 is a better option. } 13. h4
{ was first played by Nepomniatchi against Wang Hao, scoring a full point in the 2020 Candidates tournament. Nepo's immediate idea is to support Ng5, noting that the h-pawn can later be pushed to weaken Black's kingside. }
13... Nc7 14. Ng5
{ The attack on the h7 pawn forces a concession.   14.Ne3  N  with the idea Bxd6 followed by Nf5 fails to give White anything tangible.  14...Ne6  15.Bxd6  Bxd6  16.g3  Re8  17.Re2  h5  18.Rae1=  18...Qd7  19.Nf5  White got his knight to f5 but it's short-lived.  19...g6  20.Nxd6  Qxd6=  and Black will eventually equalize by swapping rooks on the e-file. }
14... g6 { The novel } 15. Nh2
{ is a very interesting suggestion by Stockfish, which ranks it as its top choice at high depth. This knight can head to g4 and, compared to Ne3, keeps the e-file open.   15.Ne3  was Wesley So's choice in the 2021 Opera Euro Rapid and is analyzed as analternative recommendation. It's an easier to learn, less demanding option that still asks some questions  (albeit less challenging than the text)  . }
15... Nce8
{ with the idea ...Ng7 to stop h4-h5 is a standard maneuver in these structures. Here it doesn't work for a very concrete and unique reason. }
16. Ng4 { Threatens to jump into h6, which Black can parry with } 16... Nf5
{ Or can he? } 17. Qxf5
{ Nope! This stunning queen sacrifice takes Stockfish only milliseconds to find, but that does not detract the slightest from its beauty.   It's almost unbelievable we're able to sacrifice a queen in one of the mainlines of the Petroff. Who said it was a boring defense?   Note: there is no real need to remember the following variations in this trainable line. You can work these out over the board knowing that White is winning. }
17... gxf5 18. Nh6+ { flushes out Black's king. } 18... Kg7
{ 18...Kh8?  loses on the spot to  19.Nhxf7++-  which wins back the queen with tons of extra material. }
19. Nxf5+ { Black's king is forced up the board again. } 19... Kg6
{ drops material with check to   19...Kg8??  20.Rxe7+-  is lights out. Black is defenseless against the following threat  20...--  21.Nh6+  Kg7  22.Ne6+  Kh8  23.Nxd8+- }
20. Nxe7+ Kg7 21. Nf5+ Kg6 22. g4
{ White is now threatening mate in two with h5+ followed by Nxh7#. The only way for Black to stay in the game is to give up another minor piece with }
22... Nf6 23. h5+ Nxh5 24. Ne7+ Kg7 25. gxh5
{ White has 3 pieces for the queen and a winning attack to boot. The following is a very aesthetically pleasing finale: }
25... Kh8 26. Re6 { is a remarkable move! } 26... f6
{ The rook is untouchable as  26...fxe6  27.Be5+  Rf6  28.Bxf6  is checkmate! }
27. Rae1 { As always, be sure to invite everyone to the party! } 27... Qd7 28.
h6 { Black is now defenseless against Rxf6. For example } 28... Rae8 29. Rxf6
Rxf6 30. Nf7+
{ Deflecting Black's rook from the f6 square spells the end for Black. } 30...
Rxf7 31. Be5+ Rg7+ 32. hxg7#
{ is the cherry on top of the cake! There is no point in training this variation @@StartBracket@@feel free to pause this trainable line straight away@@EndBracket@@ but I couldn't resist showing it! }
