16. Nxf7 { tearing apart the King's pawn shield. } 16... Kxf7
{ is the correct recapture. } 17. Ng4
{ White's pieces are now swarming in and Black must walk a tightrope to survive this. }
17... Nf5 18. Bxh6
{ Picks up a second pawn with a tempo on Black's rook. Not only that, our knight is ready to jump into e5. }
18... Re8 19. Ne5+ Kg8 20. Bf4 { Gets the bishop out of danger. } 20... Bd6
{ 20...Nxh4??  loses to  21.Nxg6  when the knight is untouchable as  21...Nxg6  22.Qxg6+  Kh8  23.Re5+-  threatens to end the game with Rh5. It's actually forced mate in 10! }
21. Bg5
{ hits Black's queen and gives White the initiative. We're ready to pick up a third pawn with Nxg6 next, getting full compensation for the piece.   Stockfish insists this position is equal, shooting an endless string of zeros. While this is true in a higher chess sense, practically White's position is far easier to play. Black's king is very exposed and he has to find a series of only moves to maintain the balance.   A sample line with accurate play by both sides is  21...Qc8  22.Nxg6  Now  22...Re4!  is an important move, stopping White's pieces from flooding in.  23.Rxe4  dxe4  24.Qxe4  Qe6  25.Ne5  Nxd4!  is another hard move to spot from a distance. Black is still not out of the woods as after  26.Re1  Bxe5  27.Qxe5  Qxe5  28.Rxe5  Nxc2  29.Re7  Rc8  30.g4=  I suspect nobody would ever take Black here. Three connected passed pawns combined with threats against Black's king give White great practical chances of scoring a full point, even if Black can hold with best play. }
