[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Petroff | 5...d5 6...Bd6"]
[Black "The problems with 9. Nc3 - Part 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. c4
c6
{ The purpose of this informational line is to point out the critical continuations after }
9. Nc3
{ which is White's most popular move. I opted to not recommend this move as I was unable to find any trace of a White advantage in the following critical line:   9.Qc2  is mymain recommendation. }
9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Bf5 12. Bg5
{ 12.Ng5  fails to give White anything after  12...h6  13.Qf3  Bg6  14.Ne4  Bxh2+!  15.Kxh2  Qh4+  16.Qh3  Qxh3+  17.gxh3  Bxe4=  was a position Wang Hao and Caruana had no trouble holding in two 2018 games vs Maxime Vachier Lagrave. }
12... Qa5 13. Nh4
{ Had a small surge in popularity in 2018/2019 when Anish Giri defeated Caruana in the 2018 Baden-Baden tournament.    Several high-level correspondence games since have demonstrated Black is fully equal after }
13... Be6 14. Bxe6 Qxg5 15. Nf3 Qa5
{ The text is stronger than Caruana's choice of  15...Qd8  in the aforementioned game. The queen is far more active on a5, keeping tabs on the c3 pawn. }
16. Bb3
{ 16.Qb3  occurred several correspondence games, an example being ½-½ @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Conde Poderoso,A @@StartBracket@@2367@@EndBracket@@-Hofer,R @@StartBracket@@2370@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018. Black played  16...Qc7  but even simpler is  16...Qb6  N  transfering the game to a harmless opposite-colored bishop endgame. }
16... Nd7 17. Qd3 Rae8
{ 17...Nf6  is another good option. White got absolutely nothing in the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@26@@EndBracket@@ Zawadzka,J @@StartBracket@@2407@@EndBracket@@-Koneru,H @@StartBracket@@2548@@EndBracket@@ Khanty-Mansiysk 2018, which continued  18.Rfe1  Rae8  19.g3  g6  20.Kg2  Kg7=  with full equality. }
18. g3 g6 19. Kg2 Nf6 20. Rae1 Kg7 21. Rxe8 Rxe8 22. Rb1 c5
{ fully equalized in the correspondence game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Massy,G @@StartBracket@@2185@@EndBracket@@-Deskin,G @@StartBracket@@2186@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018.   Conclusion: White has no hopes for an advantage in the 9. Nc3 13. Nh4 variation. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Petroff | 5...d5 6...Bd6"]
[Black "The problems with 9. Nc3 - Part 2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. c4
c6
{ The purpose of this informational line is to point out the critical continuations after }
9. Nc3
{ which is White's most popular move. I opted to not recommend this move as I was unable to find any trace of a White advantage in the following critical line:   9.Qc2  is mymain recommendation. }
9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Bf5 12. Bg5
{ 12.Ng5  fails to give White anything after  12...h6  13.Qf3  Bg6  14.Ne4  Bxh2+  lures White's king to h2  15.Kxh2  so that  15...Qh4+  picks up the e4 knight with check.  16.Qh3  Qxh3+  17.gxh3  Bxe4=  was a position Wang Hao and Caruana had no trouble holding in two 2018 games vs Maxime Vachier Lagrave. }
12... Qa5 13. d5
{ is an OTB novelty but carries little to no surprise value as it was well addressed in the 2020 Petroff repertoire book Playing the Petroff by GM Swapnil Dhopade. I failed to find any improvement for White over the analysis contained therein, which goes }
13... Be4 { forcing White to take on c6. } 14. dxc6 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Nxc6
{ White has the two bishops but no hopes for an advantage with the compromised queenside pawn structure. For example }
16. Bd5 { is well met by } 16... Rae8
{ with the idea ...Re5, which Sethuraman failed to consider in his 1.e4 Lifetime Repertoire. This strong move completely neutralizes Sethuraman's repertoire. }
17. Rfd1 Ne7 { Forces White to part with one of his bishops. } 18. Bxe7
{ 18.Be3  Nxd5  19.Qxd5  Qxd5  20.Rxd5  Bb8=  White's split queenside pawns mean Black has no issues whatsoever. }
18... Rxe7 19. Bxb7 { does not win a pawn because of } 19... Bxh2+ 20. Kxh2
Qc7+ 21. Kg1 Qxb7
{ with a completely equal endgame.   Conclusion: 13. d5 is novel but not challenging. Overall, 9. Nc3 gives White zero chances for an opening advantage. }
