5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Bd6
{ In this setup, Black abstains from exerting pressure against White's center with 6...Nc6. Instead, he prefers to reinforce the d5-pawn with ...c6 in the near future. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4
{ is almost invariably played. The only way to put pressure on Black's position is to undermine the e4 knight and d5 pawn. This move is especially effective when Black develops his bishop to d6 as his control over the d5 pawn is reduced.   8.Nbd2  fails to put enough pressure on Black's e4 knight, which can be easily reinforced with ...Bf5 and ...Re8. For example  8...Bf5  9.Re1  Re8  10.Nf1  Bg6  11.Ne3  c6  12.c4  Nf6  13.Bxg6  hxg6  14.Qb3  Qb6=  fully equalized in the top level game 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2768@@EndBracket@@ -Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2822@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2018. }
8... c6 9. Qc2 Bg4
{ has been tried a few dozen times, but runs into the tempo-gaining move } 10.
Ne5 { Hitting Black's bishop and threatening a fork with f3. } 10... Be6
{ is the best square for the bishop and has only been played once so far.   10...Bf5  walks straight into a pin, immediately dropping material to  11.f3  Bxe5  12.dxe5  Qb6+  13.c5  Nxc5  14.Bxf5  Nb3+  15.Kh1  Black resigned in the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@15@@EndBracket@@ Oechslein,R @@StartBracket@@2291@@EndBracket@@-Schydlowski,H  @@StartBracket@@1890@@EndBracket@@ GER email 2008. The point is that  15...Nxa1  loses to  16.Bxh7+  Kh8  17.Qf5+-  when Black has no good way of dealing with the threat of Qh5.   10...Bh5  is also not a good square for the bishop. After  11.cxd5  cxd5  12.Nc3  Bxe5  13.dxe5  Nxc3  14.bxc3  Bg6  15.Be3±  White's dark-squared bishop is clearly superior to Black's knight.   10...Bxe5?  loses material to  11.dxe5  Na6  12.cxd5  N  cxd5  13.Bxe4  dxe4  14.Qxe4±  leaves White with a healthy extra pawn. }
11. Nc3
{ is a natural move and a novelty, improving over the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@60@@EndBracket@@ Romieux,S @@StartBracket@@2284@@EndBracket@@-Lewis,J @@StartBracket@@2147@@EndBracket@@ Nimes 2009. }
11... f5
{ 11...Bxe5?!  drops a pawn to  12.dxe5  Na6  13.Bxe4  dxe4  14.Nxe4± } 12. Ne2
{ heading to f4 gives White the upper hand.   A sample continuation is  12...Qe7  13.Nf4  Na6  14.Nxe6  Qxe6  15.cxd5  cxd5  16.Bxa6  bxa6  17.f3  boots Black's knight with a clear advantage. Black has little to show for his compromised queenside pawn structure. }
