1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Bd6
{ In this setup, Black abstains from exerting pressure against White's center with 6...Nc6. Instead, he prefers to reinforce the d5-pawn with ...c6 in the near future. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4
{ is almost invariably played. The only way to put pressure on Black's position is to undermine the e4 knight and d5 pawn. This move is especially effective when Black develops his bishop to d6 as his control over the d5 pawn is reduced.   8.Nbd2  fails to put enough pressure on Black's e4 knight, which can be easily reinforced with ...Bf5 and ...Re8. For example  8...Bf5  9.Re1  Re8  10.Nf1  Bg6  11.Ne3  c6  12.c4  Nf6  13.Bxg6  hxg6  14.Qb3  Qb6=  fully equalized in the top level game 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2768@@EndBracket@@ -Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2822@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2018. }
8... c6 9. Qc2 Bf5
{ is third most popular but objectively dubious. Black reinforces the e4 knight but voluntarily walks into a pin. }
10. Nc3 { immediately undermines Black's knight. Coming up is Re1. } 10... Na6
{ 10...Re8  is another possible move order.  11.Re1  Na6   11...Bb4?!  is strongly met by  12.Bg5  which wins material after the following forced sequence  12...Nxg5  13.Rxe8+  Qxe8  14.Nxg5  Bxd3  15.Qxd3  g6  16.cxd5  Bxc3  17.dxc6  Qxc6  18.bxc3+-   Finally  11...Nxc3??  loses material to  12.Rxe8+  Qxe8  13.Bxf5  Ne4  14.Qb3+-  with a double-attack on the b7 and d5 pawns.  12.a3  transposes to the text. }
11. a3 { Puts an end to any ...Nb4 shenanigans. } 11... Re8 12. Re1
{ Piles on the e4 knight. } 12... Bg4
{ Steps out of the pin with the idea of spoiling White's structure with Bxf3.   12...h6  runs into  13.Nxe4  dxe4  14.Bxe4  Qe7  which would be clever if not for  15.Bg5!  Qxe4  loses material to   15...Bxh2+  can be met with  16.Kxh2  Bxe4  17.Bxe7  Bxc2  18.Rac1  Bf5  19.d5  cxd5  20.cxd5+=  left White with a strong passer in the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@ Hatzl,J @@StartBracket@@2496@@EndBracket@@-Larsen,L @@StartBracket@@2448@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2009.  16.Rxe4  Bxe4  17.Qb3  hxg5  18.Nxg5±  when Black doesn't have enough for the Queen.   12...Bg6  13.Nxe4  dxe4  14.Bxe4  Qe7  15.Bg5!  is very similar to the line above.   12...Nxc3  is strongly met by the intermezzo  13.Bxf5  Rxe1+  14.Nxe1  Ne4  15.Bxe4  dxe4  16.Qxe4  and Black is a pawn down with no compensation. }
13. cxd5
{ is White's strongest move and a novelty, improving over the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@21@@EndBracket@@ Magem Badals,J @@StartBracket@@2534@@EndBracket@@-Fluvia Poyatos,J @@StartBracket@@2498@@EndBracket@@ Barcelona 2017. Following }
13... cxd5 14. Bg5 Qc7
{ Worse is  14...f6  as after  15.Be3  Rc8  16.Nd2+-  White will pick up a pawn with Bxe4. }
15. Nxe4 { nets White a pawn. } 15... dxe4 16. Qxc7 Nxc7 17. Bxe4
{ Black has very little to show for the pawn deficit. } *

