1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Bd6
{ In this setup, Black abstains from exerting pressure against White's center with 6...Nc6. Instead, he prefers to reinforce the d5-pawn with ...c6 in the near future. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4
{ is almost invariably played. The only way to put pressure on Black's position is to undermine the e4 knight and d5 pawn. This move is especially effective when Black develops his bishop to d6 as his control over the d5 pawn is reduced.   8.Nbd2  fails to put enough pressure on Black's e4 knight, which can be easily reinforced with ...Bf5 and ...Re8. For example  8...Bf5  9.Re1  Re8  10.Nf1  Bg6  11.Ne3  c6  12.c4  Nf6  13.Bxg6  hxg6  14.Qb3  Qb6=  fully equalized in the top level game 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2768@@EndBracket@@ -Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2822@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2018. }
8... c6 9. Qc2 Na6
{ Having examined the alternatives, it's now time to turn our attention to Black's best and overwhelmingly most common option. }
10. a3
{ is correct, stopping ...Nb4.   And not  10.Bxe4?!  dxe4  11.Qxe4  Re8=  which gives Black excellent compensation for the pawn deficit. }
10... f5
{ entrenches the knight on e4 but weakens the e5 square. Play will revolve around whether White can exploit this. }
11. Nc3 Nc7 12. Re1
{ stops ...Be6. This rare move was not covered in the book Playing the Petroff by GM Swapnil Dhopade. While it doesn't guarantee White an advantage, it sets several practical problems and requires Black to be very precise to maintain the balance.   The immediate  12.b4  allows  12...Nxc3  13.Qxc3  dxc4  14.Bxc4+  Be6=  fully equalizing. This is the move Re1 is meant to prevent. }
12... Kh8
{ 12...Qf6  can be met with  13.cxd5  when  13...Nxc3?!  14.bxc3  Nxd5  15.c4+-  gave White a decisive advantage in the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Achilles, E @@StartBracket@@2412@@EndBracket@@-Puleston,T @@StartBracket@@1721@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2013. The point is that after  15...Ne7  White can push ahead with  16.c5  Bc7  17.Bg5+-  winning Black's knight on e7. }
13. b4 Bd7 { White can immediately expand with } 14. c5
{ gaining space and pushing back Black's bishop. } 14... Be7
{ This position occurred in the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Shanava,K @@StartBracket@@2401@@EndBracket@@ -Alaybeyoglu,H @@StartBracket@@2154@@EndBracket@@ Kocaeli 2002. Here I'd like to propose the novel }
15. Ne2
{ with the idea Bb2 and Ne5, followed by f3 to boot Black's knight.   By removing the knight from c3, we don't give Black the option of playing ...Nxc3, ensuring the knight will have to retreat when we play f3. Avoiding exchanges makes perfect sense since Black has much less space. }
15... Bf6 16. Bb2 Ne6 17. Ne5
{ Next up is f3 extricating Black's knight from e4. White's is slightly better thanks to the space advantage on the queenside and strong knight on e5. }
