1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Bd6
{ In this setup, Black abstains from exerting pressure against White's center with 6...Nc6. Instead, he prefers to reinforce the d5-pawn with ...c6 in the near future. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4
{ is almost invariably played. The only way to put pressure on Black's position is to undermine the e4 knight and d5 pawn. This move is especially effective when Black develops his bishop to d6 as his control over the d5 pawn is reduced.   8.Nbd2  fails to put enough pressure on Black's e4 knight, which can be easily reinforced with ...Bf5 and ...Re8. For example  8...Bf5  9.Re1  Re8  10.Nf1  Bg6  11.Ne3  c6  12.c4  Nf6  13.Bxg6  hxg6  14.Qb3  Qb6=  fully equalized in the top level game 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2768@@EndBracket@@ -Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2822@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2018. }
8... c6 9. Qc2 Na6
{ Having examined the alternatives, it's now time to turn our attention to Black's best and overwhelmingly most common option. }
10. a3
{ is correct, stopping ...Nb4.   And not  10.Bxe4?!  dxe4  11.Qxe4  Re8=  which gives Black excellent compensation for the pawn deficit. }
10... Bg4 { is Black's most common continuation. } 11. Ne5
{ Centralizes the knight with a tempo on Black's bishop.   11.Bxe4?!  does not win a pawn as after  11...dxe4  12.Qxe4  Bxf3  13.Qxf3  Qh4  with a double-attack on the h2 and d4 pawns restores material equality. }
11... Bf5
{ has been played dozens of times at the very top level. Black's idea is to play ...Bxe5 and then follow up with ...Nac5. }
12. b4
{ puts an end to any ideas of ...Nac5. Black's knight on a6 is now out of the game. }
12... f6 { is a natural move, kicking back our powerful knight on e5. } 13. Nf3
Qe8
{ 13...Re8  is not an improvement.  14.c5  Bb8  15.Nc3±  gave White a big advantage in the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@34@@EndBracket@@ Gabris,V @@StartBracket@@2312@@EndBracket@@-Cipka,I @@StartBracket@@2405@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2009. Black's position is very cramped and his pieces are uncoordinated. }
14. c5 { gives White a big space advantage on the queenside. } 14... Bb8
{ 14...Bc7  changes very little. After  15.Nc3  Qg6  16.Nh4±  White is clearly for choice. }
15. Nc3 Bg6 16. Nh4
{ Prepares to boot Black's knight with f3 next. White has a big space advantage and is thus clearly for choice. }
