6... Bd6
{ In this setup, Black abstains from exerting pressure against White's center with 6...Nc6. Instead, he prefers to reinforce the d5-pawn with ...c6 in the near future. }
7. O-O O-O 8. c4
{ is almost invariably played. The only way to put pressure on Black's position is to undermine the e4 knight and d5 pawn. This move is especially effective when Black develops his bishop to d6 as his control over the d5 pawn is reduced.   8.Nbd2  fails to put enough pressure on Black's e4 knight, which can be easily reinforced with ...Bf5 and ...Re8. For example  8...Bf5  9.Re1  Re8  10.Nf1  Bg6  11.Ne3  c6  12.c4  Nf6  13.Bxg6  hxg6  14.Qb3  Qb6=  fully equalized in the top level game 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2768@@EndBracket@@ -Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2822@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2018. }
8... c6 9. Qc2 Na6
{ Having examined the alternatives, it's now time to turn our attention to Black's best and overwhelmingly most common option. }
10. a3
{ is correct, stopping ...Nb4.  And not   10.Bxe4?!  dxe4  11.Qxe4  Re8=  which gives Black excellent compensation for the pawn deficit. }
10... Bg4 { is Black's most common continuation. } 11. Ne5
{ 11.Bxe4?!  does not win a pawn as after  11...dxe4  12.Qxe4  Bxf3  13.Qxf3  Qh4  with a double-attack on the h2 and d4 pawns restores material equality. }
11... Bf5
{ has been played dozens of times at the very top level. Black's idea is to play ...Bxe5 and then follow up with ...Nac5. }
12. b4
{ puts an end to any ideas of ...Nc5. Black's knight on a6 is now out of the game. }
12... Nc7
{ was first played by Caruana in the 2018 Wijk aan Zee tournament against Anand. It didn't gain much of a following, not only because Anand won the game, but rather because Black cannot fully equalize. }
13. f3 Bg6 { was Caruana's point. The knight on e4 is untouchable. } 14. Be3
{ is a key novelty that guarantees White an advantage. IM Christof Sielecki did not consider this option in the Chessable course Fight 1.e4 like Caruana. By taking control over the d4 square, we're now threatening to win the knight on e4.   But not  14.fxe4?  Bxe5  15.dxe5  dxe4  The point is White has no time for  16.Bxe4  because of  16...Qd4+  when Black is winning. }
14... Ng5
{ Worse is  14...Nf6  as after  15.Nxg6  hxg6  16.c5  Be7  17.Nc3+=  White has a long-lasting advantage with the bishop pair and extra queenside space. }
15. Nxg6 fxg6
{ The alternative recapture  15...hxg6  can be met with  16.c5  Be7  17.Nc3  Nge6  18.Ne2  Re8  19.a4⩲  with good prospects on the queenside. }
16. Nc3 { Black's best move is } 16... Bf4 { and after } 17. Bxf4 Rxf4 18. cxd5
Nxd5 19. Ne2 Rf8 20. Bc4
{ Next up is Nc3-e4. If Black's g6 pawn were back on f7, Black would be OK as he could challenge our knight. As it stands though, White is at least slightly better. }
