1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Nc6
{ is Black's most popular move. The second player opts to pressure our d4 pawn instead of worrying about the knight on e4. Another point behind Black's knight placement is to meet c4 with ...Nb4. }
7. O-O Bg4 8. c4
{ Anyway! Yes, our d4 pawn is slightly vulnerable because of the pin. More importantly, however, is how unstable Black's knight on e4 is. }
8... Nf6
{ is 4x as popular as the alternatives. Black decides the knight is too unstable on e4 and retreats it to f6, increasing his control over the d5 square. }
9. Nc3
{ is very strong. We sacrifice the d4-pawn to generate a big initiative, taking advantage of our lead in development. }
9... Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Nxd4 11. Qh3
{ is the best position for the queen. In the 1986 Kasparov-Karpov Match, White played Qe3+. However, the queen is much better placed on h3, keeping tabs on the h7 pawn @@StartBracket@@which will make it hard for Black to castle@@EndBracket@@ and eyeing the e6 square @@StartBracket@@which is the natural retreating square for Black's d4 knight@@EndBracket@@. }
11... dxc4 { is 3 times as popular as the alternatives. } 12. Bxc4 Be7
{ Even with simple development, Black will end up significantly worse. } 13.
Bg5 O-O
{ is most sensible, getting the king off the e-file. Less critical alternatives are given below.   •Heading for an endgame with  13...Qd7  14.Qxd7+  Nxd7  does not help much. White still retains a lot of pressure with  15.Rfe1  Nf6  16.Rxe7+  Kxe7  17.Nd5+  Kd6  18.Nxf6  gxf6  19.Bxf6±  left White with two bishops vs a rook, a material advantage White easily converted in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Matusek,J @@StartBracket@@2245@@EndBracket@@-Sirotti,C @@StartBracket@@2144@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2017.   •  13...Qc8  also fails to solve Black's problems. After  14.Qe3  Nf5  15.Qe5±  Black is in dire straits with Rfe1, Rad1, Bd3 and Nb5 coming next. }
14. Rfe1
{ with the idea Rad1 gives White a big initiative. A key tactical resource in some lines is Rxe7 followed by Nd5. This position was only reached in a handful of games so I see no point in learning any more moves, preferring to instead give a few sample continuations that prove White's advantage below.   14...Nc2??  loses on the spot to  15.Rxe7  Qxe7  16.Nd5+−   14...Re8  15.Rad1  h6  drops a pawn to  16.Bxh6  The point is  16...gxh6?  loses to  17.Qxh6  Qd6  18.Qg6+  Kh8  19.Bxf7+-  Black is busted with Rd3-h3 coming next.   14...Qd6  15.Rxe7!  is the start of a nice tactical sequence designed to open up Black's king.  15...Qxe7  16.Nd5  Qe5  17.Bxf6  gxf6  18.Qh6  Nxf6+ is now a decisive threat so Black must give back material with  18...Nf3+  19.gxf3  Qg5+  20.Qxg5+  fxg5  21.Bb3±  The two minor pieces are far stronger than Black's rook. White had little trouble converting his advantage in the correspondence game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Schmielewski,F @@StartBracket@@2033@@EndBracket@@-Cook,P @@StartBracket@@2022@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2015. }
