[White "7. Petroff | 5...d5 6...Nc6"]
[Black "7...Be7 8...Nd6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Nc6
{ is Black's most popular move. The second player opts to pressure our d4 pawn instead of worrying about the knight on e4. Another point behind Black's knight placement is to meet c4 with ...Nb4. }
7. O-O Be7
{ is Black's most popular move and the absolute main line of the Petroff. } 8.
Nbd2
{ is the modern main line and a very practical choice. It has far less theory than the more common alternatives 8. c4 and 8. Re1 and gives White larger chances for an advantage.   This move was not considered in the book Opening Repertoire: The Petroff Defense by IM Cyrus Lakdawala nor in the book A Vigorous Chess Opening Repertoire for Black by FM Or Cohen.  Additionally, the book The Petroff-Move by Move by IM Cyrus Lakdawala also did not cover this move. }
8... Nd6 { Retreating the knight is too cooperative. } 9. c3 Bf5
{ Here I'd like to recommend the strong and novel } 10. Bc2
{ with the idea Bb3 to attack the d5 pawn. This forces Black to swap off with }
10... Bxc2
{ 10...Qd7  allows White to improve the light-squared bishop with  11.Ba4  with the big threat of Ne5, effectively forcing  11...b5  but this greatly weakens Black's queenside. White can simply drop back with  12.Bb3  Be6  13.Re1⩲  with a stable advantage. Coming up is Nf1 followed by Bf4.   Similarly  10...O-O  fails to stop White from improving the bishop with  11.Bb3  with good pressure on the  d5  pawn. For example  11...Ne4   11...Be6  is another option when  12.Re1  Bf6  13.Nf1  Ne7  14.Ng3⩲  gives White the better game.  12.Re1  Nxd2  13.Bxd2⩲  followed by Ne5 gives White the upper hand. }
11. Qxc2 Bf6
{ is not a move Black wanted to play but the alternatives aren't any better.   The point is the desirable  11...O-O ??  loses a pawn to  12.Qb3+-  with a double-attack on the b7 and d5 pawns.   11...Nb8  with the idea of meeting  12.Qb3  with  12...c6  is also possible. Now  13.Re1  O-O  14.Nf1⩲  followed by Bf4 gives White a slight advantage. }
12. Re1+ Ne7 13. Nf1 O-O 14. Bf4
{ gives White a slight advantage. Black is quite solid but we can press with ideas like a4-a5, gaining space on the queenside, or alternatively doubling on the e-file with Re2 followed by Rae1. }
