1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Nc6
{ is Black's most popular move. The second player opts to pressure our d4 pawn instead of worrying about the knight on e4. Another point behind Black's knight placement is to meet c4 with ...Nb4. }
7. O-O Be7
{ is Black's most popular move and the absolute main line of the Petroff. } 8.
Nbd2
{ is the modern main line and a very practical choice. It has far less theory than the more common alternatives 8. c4 and 8. Re1 and gives White larger chances for an advantage. }
8... Bf5 { is second most common. } 9. Re1
{ This move was not considered in Chessbase FritzTrainer The Reliable Petroff - An Evergreen Elite Choice by GM Daniel Fernandez.  Black has two options now: retreating the knight with 9...Nd6 or capturing our knight on d2. }
9... Nd6 10. Nf1
{ Clears the way for Bf4. The knight on f1 can later be relocated to e3 or g3. }
10... O-O 11. Bf4
{ is a good, active square for the bishop that also threatens to win a piece with Bxd6 followed by Bxf5. }
11... Bxd3
{ 11...Be6  is very passive. After  12.c3  Qd7  13.Qc2  g6  14.Ne3±  White started a big attack with h4, Ng5 and h5, going on to win in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@59@@EndBracket@@ Anton Guijarro,D  @@StartBracket@@2694@@EndBracket@@ -Smeets,J @@StartBracket@@2585@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2020. This game is analyzed in themodel games section. }
12. Qxd3
{ gave White a big advantage in the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@113@@EndBracket@@ Tabatabaei,M @@StartBracket@@2629@@EndBracket@@ -Kuzubov,Y @@StartBracket@@2643@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020.  All of our minor pieces are superior to Black's counterparts. The d5 pawn is about to come under pressure with Ne3 and this knight can also jump into f5 later on. }
