1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Nc6
{ is Black's most popular move. The second player opts to pressure our d4 pawn instead of worrying about the knight on e4. Another point behind Black's knight placement is to meet c4 with ...Nb4. }
7. O-O Be7
{ is Black's most popular move and the absolute main line of the Petroff. } 8.
Nbd2
{ is the modern main line and a very practical choice. It has far less theory than the more common alternatives 8. c4 and 8. Re1 and gives White larger chances for an advantage. }
8... Nxd2 { is at least 4x as common as the alternatives. } 9. Bxd2 Bg4
{ 9...O-O  10.c3  Bg4  is covered via the9...Bg4 10.c3 O-O move order. } 10. c3
{ severely restricts Black's knight on c6 and clears the way for Qb3 later on. }
10... Qd7 11. Bf4 g5
{ is enterprising but objectively very dubious. With his king still in the center, Black has no time for such shenanigans. }
12. Bg3
{ improves over the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Jakovenko,D @@StartBracket@@2698@@EndBracket@@ -Wang,Y @@StartBracket@@2674@@EndBracket@@ China 2019. }
12... f5
{ with the idea f4 to trap our dark-squared bishop is Black's idea behind 11...g5. Worry not, White emerges with a clear edge after }
13. h3 Bh5 14. Be2
{ is a very strong retreating move. White's threat is Nxg5 taking advantage of the fact that Black's bishop on h5 is unprotected and his king is still on e8. }
14... O-O-O
{ Going to the other side of the board with  14...O-O  is worse as Black's king ends up very exposed after  15.Ne5  Nxe5  16.Bxe5  Bxe2  17.Qxe2±  Black will now be wishing his f and g-pawns were back on their starting position. }
15. Ne5 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Bxe2 17. Qxe2 Rhg8 18. Qh5
{ is a great position for the queen, stopping Black's attack before it even got started. Black's advanced f and g-pawns are nothing but targets as Black can't open up the position. For example }
18... g4 19. h4
{ leaves White with a monster bishop on e5 and a clear target on f5. White is clearly for choice. }
