11. h3
{ Prepares to break the annoying pin. This move was not covered in the book The Petroff - an expert repertoire for Black by GM Konstantin Sakaev. }
11... Bh5
{ is the only good reply.   Taking a knight is a mistake  11...Bxf3?!  12.Qxf3  In the game 1-0 Zilka, Stepan @@StartBracket@@2530@@EndBracket@@ vs Penz, Harald @@StartBracket@@2308@@EndBracket@@ 2018. Black tried  12...Bd6  and quickly got into trouble after  13.Rae1  Ne7  14.Re2  Qd7  15.Rfe1  c6  16.Qh5  g6  17.Qh4  f6  18.Re6+-   Retreating with  11...Be6  is also no good. Following  12.Re1  a6  13.Re2  Qd7  14.Bf4  Bd6  15.Bxd6  Qxd6  16.Ng5  g6  White now has  17.Rxe6!  fxe6  followed by  18.Nxh7!  crashing through.  18...Rf7  19.Ng5  Rf6  20.Qg4  Kg7  21.f4  Raf8  22.g3+-  with full control and a decisive advantage. }
12. g3
{ is an idea we've seen before. White wants to edge the king up to g2, covering the f3 knight, in order to develop the queen with Qc2. }
12... Qd7 { 12...Bg6  13.Qc2  Qd7  14.Kg2  has little independent value. } 13.
Kg2 a6 { is a big mistake as White has the tactical shot } 14. Ne5 Bxd1 15.
Nxd7 Rfd8 16. Raxd1 Rxd7 17. f4
{ The smoke has cleared and White ended up with the two bishops and a big space advantage. }
17... Na5
{ This position was reached in the game ½-½ @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@ Yu,Y @@StartBracket@@2738@@EndBracket@@-Bu,X @@StartBracket@@2705@@EndBracket@@ Ningbo 2019, where White played 18. Rfe1. Better is }
18. b3
{ stopping ...Nc4. The engines are already claiming White has a decisive advantage here with g4 and f5 coming next. }
