[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Petroff | 5...d5 6...Nc6"]
[Black "7...Be7 8...Nxd2 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4
{ Black may look to be ahead in development, having already moved his d-pawn and centralized his knight. However, appearances are deceptive as the knight on e4 is a target, which will allow us to develop with tempi. }
5. d4 d5
{ is by far Black's most common move. The second player takes a stake in the center and establishes his knight on e4. }
6. Bd3
{ If Black's knight were on f6 instead of e4, this would be a position from the Exchange French. While this may seem like an improved version for Black, the knight on e4 is a target. We'll be undermining it with moves like Re1, c4, Qc2 and/or Nbd2/Nc3 depending on Black's setup. }
6... Nc6
{ is Black's most popular move. The second player opts to pressure our d4 pawn instead of worrying about the knight on e4. Another point behind Black's knight placement is to meet c4 with ...Nb4. }
7. O-O Be7
{ is Black's most popular move and the absolute main line of the Petroff. } 8.
Nbd2
{ is the modern main line and a very practical choice. It has far less theory than the more common alternatives 8. c4 and 8. Re1 and gives White larger chances for an advantage. }
8... Nxd2 { is at least 4x as common as the alternatives. } 9. Bxd2 Bg4
{ 9...O-O  10.c3  Bg4  transposes to 9...Bg4 10.c3 O-O. } 10. c3
{ severely restricts Black's knight on c6 and clears the way for Qb3 later on. }
10... O-O
{ 10...Bh5  has little independent value.  11.h3  O-O  12.g3  transposes to the text. }
11. h3
{ Prepares to break the annoying pin. This move was not in the book The Petroff - an expert repertoire for White by GM Konstantin Sakaev. }
11... Bh5
{ is the only good reply.   Taking a knight is a mistake  11...Bxf3?!  12.Qxf3  In the game 1-0 Zilka, Stepan @@StartBracket@@2530@@EndBracket@@ vs Penz, Harald @@StartBracket@@2308@@EndBracket@@ 2018. Black tried  12...Bd6  and quickly got into trouble after  13.Rae1  Ne7  14.Re2  Qd7  15.Rfe1  c6  16.Qh5  g6  17.Qh4  f6  18.Re6+-   Retreating with  11...Be6  is also no good. Following  12.Re1  a6  13.Re2  Qd7  14.Bf4  Bd6  15.Bxd6  Qxd6  16.Ng5  g6  White now has  17.Rxe6!  fxe6  followed by  18.Nxh7!  crashing through.  18...Rf7  19.Ng5  Rf6  20.Qg4  Kg7  21.f4  Raf8  22.g3+-  with full control and a decisive advantage. }
12. g3
{ We've seen this before. White wants to edge the king up to g2 so as to develop the queen with Qc2. }
12... Qd7 { 12...Bg6  13.Qc2  Qd7  14.Kg2  has little independent value. } 13.
Kg2 Bg6
{ 13...Rfe8  is also possible. After  14.Re1  Bd6  15.Qb3  15...Ne7  16.Nh4+=  White is slightly better and can double-up on the e-file with Re3 and Rae1 next. }
14. Bxg6
{ Black has tried both recaptures in this position. Let's start with the more conservative }
14... hxg6 15. Bf4
{ is more flexible than  15.Re1  . The bishop certainly belongs on f4 while the f1 rook can either pop out to e1 or instead head to h1 to support the h4-h5 advance depending on how Black proceeds. }
15... Rae8 16. Qd3 Nd8 17. h4
{ starts active operations on the kingside. White can follow up with Rh1 and h5 with good prospects. }
