1. e4 Nc6
{ The Nimzowitsch defense is an unusual, hypermodern opening. Black invites White to take over the center with d2-d4 with the intention of later undermining the central pawns with well-timed pawn breaks. However, we won't be allowing any such shenanigans. }
2. Nf3
{ is the simplest reply, inviting a transposition to the King's pawn game with  2...e5  In this chapter, we'll be examining Black's other options, namely }
2... d6
{ 2...g6  3.d4  Bg7  4.Nc3  d6  5.Be3  Nf6  is covered via the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Nc6  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  Nf6  4.Nc3  g6  move order.   2...Nf6?!  This Alekhine-like approach has been played in 1500+ games.   2...d5  This Scandinavian-like pawn push featured in over 2000 OTB games.   2...f5?!  is the so-called Colorado Gambit. I was surprised to find this move has been played 1000+ times.   2...e5  will be covered in an upcoming course. }
3. d4 Nf6
{ 3...g6  4.Nc3  Bg7  5.Be3  Nf6  is covered via the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Nc6  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  Nf6  4.Nc3  g6  move order.   3...e5  4.Nc3  transposes to the Philidor, which is covered inchapter 2. }
4. Nc3 Bg4
{ is Black's most common move, which has occurred in 3000+ OTB games.   4...g6  is a subpar version of the Pirc, which was seen in 1200+ games.   4...e5  5.Bb5  transposes to the Philidor, which is examined inchapter 2 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Bonus: 1...Nc6"]
[Black "2...f5 Colorado Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The Nimzowitsch defense is an unusual, hypermodern opening. Black invites White to take over the center with d2-d4 with the intention of later undermining the central pawns with well-timed pawn breaks. However, we won't be allowing any such shenanigans. }
2. Nf3
{ is the simplest reply, inviting a transposition to the King's pawn game with 2...e5. In this chapter, we'll be examining Black's other options.   2.d4  is possible but White's chances for an advantage after  2...d5  are slim. }
2... f5
{ is the so-called Colorado Gambit. It severely weakens Black's position but refuting it requires some precision. }
3. exf5 d5 4. d4
{ The key to refuting this Gambit is to not hold onto the pawn, but rather exploit the weaknesses left behind by 2...f5, namely the e5 square. White takes a stake in the center and will play Bb5 on the next turn. }
4... Bxf5
{ Restores material equality but Black is still in big trouble after } 5. Bb5
{ White is ready to undermine Black's c6 knight with Ne5, which is a phenomenal outpost for our knight. }
5... e6 6. Ne5 Ne7 7. Nc3
{ is simple and effective, continuing development. Next up is Bf4.   7.Bg5  is another good option and White's most common move.  7...Qd6  8.c3  is most common but not very accurate. After   8.c4!  is required to get an advantage but I see no need to enter the complications after  8...dxc4  9.Nc3  Bd3+=  This is the reason I prefer 7. Nc3.  8...a6  Black has decent chances. }
7... a6
{ breaking the pin is necessary.   7...Qd6?  is strongly met by  8.Bf4+-  with all sorts of threats like g4 and Ng6. Black is busted. }
8. Ba4 Rb8
{ This preparatory move is required to play ...b5.   The immediate  8...b5?  loses to  9.Nxb5!  axb5  10.Bxb5  Qd6  11.c3  g6   11...Ra6  12.Bf4!  Rb6  13.Qa4+-  is lights out.  12.Bg5+-  when Black can hardly move not to mention White is threatening to win material with g4. }
9. Bg5 Qd6 10. f4
{ Cements the knight on e5. We are ready to roll Black over with g2-g4. } 10...
b5 11. Bb3 h6 12. Bxe7 Nxe7
{ The alternative recapture  12...Bxe7  runs into  13.Qh5+± } 13. g4 Bh7 14.
Qe2
{ gives White an overwhelming position. f5 is a big threat not to mention Black can hardly complete development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Bonus: 1...Nc6"]
[Black "2...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The Nimzoswitch defense is an unusual, hypermodern opening. Black invites White to take over the center with d2-d4 with the intention of later undermining them with well-timed pawn breaks. However, we won't be allowing any such shenanigans. }
2. Nf3
{ is the simplest reply, inviting a transposition to the King's pawn game with 2...e5. In this chapter, we'll be examining Black's other options.   2.d4  is possible but White's chances for an advantage after  2...d5  are slim. }
2... Nf6
{ This Alekhine-like approach is very dubious.   2...e5  will be covered in an upcoming course. }
3. e5 Ng4
{ is not a good square for the knight.   3...Nd5  4.d4  d6  Transposes to the mainline of the Alekhine, which is covered in detail in my course Crush the Alekhine and Scandinavian!   Undeveloping the knight with  3...Ng8?!  makes zero sense.  4.d4±  takes over the center with a huge advantage. }
4. d4
{ Takes over the center and intends to follow up with h3 when Black's knight will find itself very short on squares. }
4... d6
{ Putting pressure on White's center is Black's only logical plan. Anything else and he's simply much worse. }
5. h3 Nh6 6. Nc3
{ is very precise. The idea is to meet ...dxe5 with d5!   Also possible is  6.Bxh6  gxh6  7.Nc3  but keeping the two bishops on the board is slightly more precise. }
6... a6
{ is Black's most common move, stopping Bb5.   6...dxe5?!  runs into  7.d5  Nb8  8.Nxe5±  with a big lead in development and a clear advantage. }
7. Bg5 dxe5 { has been tried a couple of times and once again runs into } 8. d5
Na7
{ 8...Nd4  9.Nxe5±  gave White a big advantage in the game 1-0 @@StartBracket@@64@@EndBracket@@ Lagarde, M @@StartBracket@@2393@@EndBracket@@-Cotonnec, M  @@StartBracket@@2276@@EndBracket@@ France 2009. }
9. Nxe5 g6 10. Qd2
{ is a funny position with Black's knights on h6 and a7. White, of course, is the only one having fun here. }
*

