[White "8. Bonus: 1...Nc6"]
[Black "2...Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The Nimzoswitch defense is an unusual, hypermodern opening. Black invites White to take over the center with d2-d4 with the intention of later undermining them with well-timed pawn breaks. However, we won't be allowing any such shenanigans. }
2. Nf3
{ is the simplest reply, inviting a transposition to the King's pawn game with 2...e5. In this chapter, we'll be examining Black's other options.   2.d4  is possible but White's chances for an advantage after  2...d5  are slim. }
2... Nf6
{ This Alekhine-like approach is very dubious.   2...e5  will be covered in an upcoming course. }
3. e5 Ng4
{ is not a good square for the knight.   3...Nd5  4.d4  d6  Transposes to the mainline of the Alekhine, which is covered in detail in my course Crush the Alekhine and Scandinavian!   Undeveloping the knight with  3...Ng8?!  makes zero sense.  4.d4±  takes over the center with a huge advantage. }
4. d4
{ Takes over the center and intends to follow up with h3 when Black's knight will find itself very short on squares. }
4... d6
{ Putting pressure on White's center is Black's only logical plan. Anything else and he's simply much worse. }
5. h3 Nh6 6. Nc3 { is very precise. The idea is to meet ...dxe5 with d5! } 6...
a6
{ is Black's most common move, stopping Bb5.   6...dxe5?!  runs into  7.d5  Nb8  8.Nxe5±  with a big lead in development and a clear advantage. }
7. Bg5 Bf5 8. Nh4
{ is White's strongest move, which was not considered in the book Play 1... Nc6! by Christoph Wisnewski. }
8... Qd7
{ occurred in 5/7 games that reached this position. Alternatives are considered below.   8...Nb4  fails to accomplish anything of value. White can just cover the c2-pawn with  9.Rc1!  dxe5  10.d5  g6  11.a3  forces  11...Nxc2+  as Black's knight was out of squares.  12.Rxc2  Bxc2  13.Qxc2+-  when White's two minor pieces are much stronger than Black's rook.   8...Bc8  can be met with  9.f4  Nf5  10.Nxf5  Bxf5  11.g4  Bd7  12.Bg2±  with an overwhelming position.   8...Bg6  is very similar.  9.f4  Nf5  10.Nxf5  Bxf5  11.g4  Bd7  12.Bg2± }
9. g4 Bg6 { 9...Be6??  10.d5+-  wins a piece } 10. d5
{ forces Black to undevelop his knight. } 10... Nd8
{ 10...Nxe5??  11.f4+-  traps Black's knight. } 11. f4
{ Threatens to win material with f5. } 11... e6 12. Qe2
{ followed by O-O-O gives White an overwhelming position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. Bonus: 1...Nc6"]
[Black "2...d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ The Nimzoswitch defense is an unusual, hypermodern opening. Black invites White to take over the center with d2-d4 with the intention of later undermining them with well-timed pawn breaks. However, we won't be allowing any such shenanigans. }
2. Nf3
{ is the simplest reply, inviting a transposition to the King's pawn game with 2...e5. In this chapter, we'll be examining Black's other options.   2.d4  is possible but White's chances for an advantage after  2...d5  are slim. }
2... d5 3. exd5 Qxd5
{ is a subpar version of the Scandinavian. The main problem with the early ...Nc6 is Black can no longer play ...c6. }
4. Nc3 Qa5
{ is Black's only sensible square for the queen.   4...Qh5  5.Nb5  creates immediate problems.  5...Kd8  is the only way to protect the c7 pawn when  6.Be2±  is much better for White.   4...Qf5  isn't much better. After  5.d4  Nb4  6.Bb5+  c6  7.Ba4±  Black's threats are over and his pieces are just scattered.   4...Qd6  is also not a good square for Black's queen as it'll be subject to Nb5 with tempo down the line.  5.d4  Nf6   5...a6?!  stops Nb5 but runs into  6.d5  Ne5  7.Be2±  with a big space advantage.  6.Nb5  6...Qd8  7.c4!  takes full control over the center with a clear advantage.   4...Qd8  5.d4±  threatens to push ahead with d5. Bf4 followed by Nb5 are also in the cards. }
5. Bb5
{ threatens to cripple Black's queenside pawn structure with Bxc6+.   5.d4  is another good option but the text is stronger. }
5... Bd7 6. a3
{ is a very strong move with the idea of meeting ...a6 with b4. } 6... a6
{ runs into } 7. b4
{ is a strong counterblow. Black's queen is very short on squares so } 7...
Nxb4
{ is practically forced.   Retreating with  7...Qb6?  loses material to  8.Nd5  Qxb5   8...Qa7  9.Nxc7+  Kd8  10.Bxc6  Kxc7  11.Bxd7+−  is lights out  9.Nxc7++-  is decisive. }
8. axb4 Qxa1 9. Bxd7+ Kxd7
{ Black's king is out in the open but more importantly } 10. Nd4
{ followed by Nb3 will trap Black's queen. White is winning. } *

[Event "?"]
