1. e4 Nc6
{ The Nimzoswitch defense is an unusual, hypermodern opening. Black invites White to take over the center with d2-d4 with the intention of later undermining them with well-timed pawn breaks. However, we won't be allowing any such shenanigans. }
2. Nf3
{ is the simplest reply, inviting a transposition to the King's pawn game with 2...e5. In this chapter, we'll be examining Black's other options.   2.d4  is possible but White's chances for an advantage after  2...d5  are slim. }
2... d5 3. exd5 Qxd5
{ is a subpar version of the Scandinavian. The main problem with the early ... Nc6 is Black can no longer play ...c6. }
4. Nc3 Qa5
{ is Black's only sensible square for the queen.   4...Qf5  isn't much better. After  5.d4  Nb4  6.Bb5+  c6  7.Ba4±  Black's threats are over and his pieces are just scattered.   4...Qh5  5.Nb5  creates immediate problems.  5...Kd8  is the only way to protect the c7 pawn when  6.Be2±  is much better for White.   4...Qd6  is not a good square for Black's queen as it'll be subject to Nb5 with tempo down the line.  5.d4  Nf6   5...a6?!  stops Nb5 but runs into  6.d5  Ne5  7.Be2±  with a big space advantage.  6.Nb5  6...Qd8  7.c4!  takes full control over the center with a clear advantage.   4...Qd8  5.d4±  threatens to push ahead with d5. Bf4 followed by Nb5 are also in the cards. }
5. Bb5
{ threatens to cripple Black's queenside pawn structure with Bxc6.   5.d4  is another good option but the text is stronger. }
5... Bd7 6. a3
{ is a very strong move with the idea of meeting ...a6 with b4. } 6... O-O-O
{ is Black's main move. } 7. Rb1
{ prepares to push ahead with b4 and a4. Black's king is already committed to the queenside and is about to come under a big attack. }
7... a6
{ 7...Nf6  8.b4  Qb6  9.a4±  followed by a5 is very strong. Black's queen has barely any squares. }
8. b4 Qb6 9. Be2
{ White will complete development with O-O, d3 and Be3. Then we can start a big attack against Black's king with b5. The pawn on a6 is a big hook and Black's queen on b6 is also very exposed. }
