1. e4 Nc6
{ The Nimzoswitch defense is an unusual, hypermodern opening. Black invites White to take over the center with d2-d4 with the intention of later undermining them with well-timed pawn breaks. However, we won't be allowing any such shenanigans. }
2. Nf3
{ is the simplest reply, inviting a transposition to the King's pawn game with 2...e5. In this chapter, we'll be examining Black's other options.   2.d4  is possible but White's chances for an advantage after  2...d5  are slim. }
2... d6
{ 2...g6  3.d4  Bg7  4.Nc3  d6  5.Be3  Nf6  is covered via the 2...d6 3.d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 g6 move order. }
3. d4 Bg4 { is well met by the direct } 4. d5
{ White has several good alternatives that give him a big advantage such as  4.c3  ,  4.Be3  and  4.Nc3 }
4... Ne5 5. Nxe5
{ is a very strong, temporary queen sacrifice. After the following forced sequence of moves }
5... Bxd1 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6
{ White is now threatening to end the game with  7...--  8.cxb7  Qd7  9.bxa8=Q  checkmate! }
7... a6 { 7...b6??  loses on the spot to  8.c7  Qd7  9.Bxd7  Checkmate! } 8.
c7+ { comes with check, ensuring White will win Black's queen. } 8... axb5 9.
cxd8=Q+ Rxd8 10. Nxf7 Kxf7 11. Kxd1
{ The smoke has cleared and White ended up with an extra pawn and the superior pawn structure. }
