1. e4 Nc6
{ The Nimzoswitch defense is an unusual, hypermodern opening. Black invites White to take over the center with d2-d4 with the intention of later undermining them with well-timed pawn breaks. However, we won't be allowing any such shenanigans. }
2. Nf3
{ is the simplest reply, inviting a transposition to the King's pawn game with 2...e5. In this chapter, we'll be examining Black's other options.   2.d4  is possible but White's chances for an advantage after  2...d5  are slim. }
2... d6
{ 2...g6  3.d4  Bg7  4.Nc3  d6  5.Be3  Nf6  is covered via the 2...d6 3.d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 g6 move order. }
3. d4 Nf6
{ 3...g6  4.Nc3  Bg7  5.Be3  Nf6  is covered via the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  Nc6  2.Nf3  d6  3.d4  Nf6  4.Nc3  g6  move order.   3...e5  4.Nc3  transposes to the Philidor, which is covered inchapter 2. }
4. Nc3 Bg4
{ tries to put pressure on the d4 pawn by pinning the f3 knight.   4...e5  5.Bb5  transposes to the Philidor, which is examined inchapter 2 }
5. Be3
{ This natural move was not considered in the book The Modernized Nimzovich Defense by GM Christian Bauer. }
5... e6
{ Black wants to play ...d5 next, achieving a French-like position with his bishop outside the pawn chain. }
6. h3 Bh5
{ 6...Bxf3  is too cooperative.  7.Qxf3+=  White has the center and bishop pair. Next up is O-O-O followed by g4-g5 with a big advantage. }
7. d5
{ Exclam! White gains a lot of space and stops Black from liberating his position with ...d6-d5. }
7... exd5 8. exd5 Ne5 9. g4
{ Starts active play on the kingside. This makes perfect sense as we'll castle long. }
9... Bg6
{ 9...Nxf3+  10.Qxf3  Bg6  11.O-O-O  ±  White is almost fully developed while Black only has two minor pieces out. It's clear that White is much better. }
10. Nd2
{ clears the way for f4-f5 with a huge advantage. Black also has to watch out for Bb5+. }
