{ The following is a game in the 6... Bf5 line of the Petroff between super-GMs Leinier Dominguez and Jan-Krzysztof Duda from the 2021 Opera Euro Rapid tournament. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Bf5 7. O-O Be7 8.
Re1 O-O 9. Nbd2 Nd6 10. Nf1 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Nd7 12. Bf4 Re8 13. Qb3 Nb6
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, specifically in the6...Bf5 variation. }
14. Ne3 c6 15. a4
{ is a typical resource in these positions. The pawn structure is symmetric but White can pressure Black's queenside by expanding with a4-a5. }
15... a5
{ Stops the a-pawn but White can now turn his attention to the other side of the board with }
16. h4 Ndc4
{ The pawn on h4 is untouchable as   16...Bxh4  17.Nxh4  Qxh4  18.Bxd6+-  wins a piece. }
17. Nf5 Bf8 18. h5
{ Gains space and establishes the knight on f5. More importantly, it vacates the h4 square allowing for N3h4 in order to swing over the queen to g3. }
18... Qd7 19. N3h4 Re6 20. Qg3
{ White has a big piece majority on the kingside and already has serious threats like Nxg7 followed by h6. Meanwhile, Black's knights are completely out of the game. }
20... Rae8 21. Rxe6 Qxe6 22. b3 { traps Black's knight. } 22... Nb2
{ 22...Nd6  is not possible because the bishop on f8 has to keep an eye on the g7 pawn.  23.Bxd6+-  Bxd6??  24.Qxg7 }
23. Rb1 g6 { does nothing as the g-pawn is pinned. } 24. Rxb2
{ White is now a piece up and easily converted after } 24... Qe1+ 25. Kh2 Qd1
26. hxg6 Re1 27. gxf7+ Kxf7 28. Qf3
{ forces the queens off the board. Black had seen enough and threw in the towel.   1-0 @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Dominguez Perez,L @@StartBracket@@2758@@EndBracket@@-Duda,J @@StartBracket@@2743@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021 }
*

[Event "?"]
