[White "9. Model games"]
[Black "1-0 (25) Areshchenko,A (2570)-Mamedyarov,S (2657) Moscow 2005"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a miniature between GMs Alexander Areschenko and Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from the 2005 Aeroflot open. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Bf5 7. c4 c6 8. O-O
Be7 9. Qc2 O-O 10. Ne5 Bd6 11. a3 Na6 12. b4 Qh4 13. Nc3
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, specifically in the8...c6 9...Na6 #3 variation. }
13... Rae8
{ 13...Nc7  covering the d5 pawn and rerouting the knight is a better option.   Is natural but inaccurate due to the following sequence of moves: }
14. cxd5 Nxc3 15. Bxf5 { wins the bishop pair. } 15... Bxe5 16. dxe5 Nxd5 17.
g3 Qh5 18. Bb2
{ The smoke has cleared and White ended up with the bishop pair, which is a great asset in this open position. Black's disadvantage is further compounded by the knight on a6 being completely out of the game. }
18... f6 19. exf6 Nxf6 20. Rae1 { White brings his last piece into the game. }
20... Nc7 21. h4 Ncd5 22. Be6+ Rxe6
{ Black couldn't stand White's strong bishops anymore and decided to sacrifice an exchange, hoping to exploit White's slightly weakened light-squares on the kingside.   22...Kh8  was better although White is still much better after  23.Re5± }
23. Rxe6 Nf4 24. Re3 Nh3+ 25. Kh2
{ is a mistake that lets Black right back into the game.   25.Kh1!  instead is the right square for the king. Following  25...Nd5  26.Qe2  Nhf4  27.Qxh5  Nxh5  28.Rb3+-  Black has no compensation whatsoever for the exchange. }
25... Nd5
{ blunders the game away. Mamedyarov didn't even wait for Areschenko to move and immediately resigned.   The point is White has the intermezzo  26.Qe2  Nhf4  27.Qc4+-  with a decisive material advantage noting that Black's d5 knight is pinned.   25...Ng4+!  however, would have maintained the balance. After  26.Kxh3  Nxe3  27.Qb3+  Nd5  Material is level and Black has no issues.  It's not every day you seem a 2600+ GM go down in 25 moves!  1-0 @@StartBracket@@25@@EndBracket@@ Areshchenko,A @@StartBracket@@2570@@EndBracket@@-Mamedyarov,S @@StartBracket@@2657@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2005 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Model games"]
[Black "1-0 (33) Le,Q (2694)-Sadhwani,R (2482) Xingtai 2019"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a model game between Vietnam's number 1, GM Le Quang Liem, and Indian GM Raunak Sadhwani. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. c4
{ 8.Nbd2  was my recommendation in thetheory section. The game eventually transposed to a position that's part of our repertoire. }
8... O-O
{ is pretty rare and gives White excellent chances for an advantage.   8...Nb4  is the move Black should go for. Practice has shown Black is fine in this variation. The mainline continues  9.Be2  O-O  10.Nc3  Bf5  11.a3  Nxc3  12.bxc3  Nc6= }
9. Nc3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Bg4 12. Re1
{ We've now transposed back into our repertoire, specifically the 7...Bg4 8...Be7 #2 variation. }
12... Bd6 13. h3 Bh5 14. g4
{ Breaks the pin with tempo. Yes, it slightly opens White's king but Black is in no position to exploit this. More importantly, White is ready to activate his pieces with Bg5 and Ne5. }
14... Bg6 15. Bg5 Qd7
{ runs into a tempo-gaining move for White.   15...Qc8  was a better option. Play could continue  16.Ne5  Re8  17.Bf4± }
16. Ne5 Qc8
{ Black's queen ended up on c8 anyway so it should have gone there on move 15. This tempo loss will turn out to be very costly.   16...Bxe5?!  is even worse. After  17.dxe5  Qxd1  18.Raxd1+−  Black is in trouble. White is threatening to invade on the 7th with  Rd7  and f4-f5 ideas are also in the air. }
17. Qf3 Bxe5
{ 17...Nxe5  is no improvement. After  18.dxe5  Bc5  19.Be3±  White is still clearly for choice. }
18. dxe5 Re8 19. Qg3
{ White is now ready to march the f-pawn up the board with f4-f5. } 19... Na5
20. Bf1
{ Provoking the weakening move c6 with   20.Bb5  c6  before returning to f1  21.Bf1  was even better. }
20... Qe6 21. f4 f5
{ drops material.   Black's position was already very difficult but  21...Qb6+  would have put up more resistance. For example  22.Qf2  Qxf2+  23.Kxf2  h6  24.Bh4  Bc2  gets the bishop out of harm's way. White is still much better but at least Black is still in the game. }
22. exf6 Qb6+ 23. Qf2 gxf6 24. Qxb6 axb6 25. Bxf6
{ White is now a clean pawn up, has the bishop pair and a passed pawn on the kingside. You get the picture, White has a decisive advantage. }
25... Bf7 26. Rxe8+ Rxe8 27. Rd1
{ Prepares to invade along the 7th rank, which Black cannot prevent. } 27...
Nc6
{ 27...Be6  fails to stop Rd7 because of  28.f5  Bxa2  when  29.Rd7  comes anyway with decisive effect. Rg7+ is now a big threat and if  29...Bf7  then simply  30.Rxc7+-  collects material with an overwhelming position. }
28. Rd7 Re6 29. g5 Re1 30. Kf2 Ra1 31. Rxc7 Rxa2+ 32. Kg3 Be6 33. f5
{ There is no stopping White's kingside pawns so Black resigned.  The pawn on f5 is untouchable as   33...Bxf5  loses the rook to  34.Bc4+  Kf8  35.Bxa2+-   33...Bd5  allows White to push ahead with  34.g6  hxg6  35.fxg6  Rc8+ is now a mate threat and if  35...Ra8  then switching sides with  36.Rh7+-  decides the game. Black is powerless against Rh8+.  1-0  (33)  Le,Q  (2694)  -Sadhwani,R  (2482)  Xingtai 2019 }
*

