{ The following is a correspondence game in the 6...Nc6 mainline of the Petroff. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8.
Nbd2 Nxd2 9. Bxd2 Bg4 10. c3 O-O 11. h3 Bh5 12. g3 Qd7 13. Kg2 Bg6 14. Bxg6
hxg6 15. Bf4 Bd6 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. h4
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, specifically in the7...Be7 8...Nxd2 #6 variation. }
17... Rae8 18. Qd3
{ heading to b5 to provoke weaknesses in Black's queenside. } 18... Re7 19.
Rfe1 Rfe8 20. Qb5 b6 21. Rxe7 Rxe7 22. b4
{ Starts active operations on the queenside - a common plan in this pawn structure. The center is locked, so White can choose to play in one of the flanks.    Making progress on the kingside is difficult. White could break with h4-h5  @@StartBracket@@prepared by Rh1@@EndBracket@@ but there's no clear way to continue afterward.   The queenside, however, is a much more promising theater of operations as Black has already weakened his position with ...b6. }
22... Nb8 23. a4 c6 24. Qd3 Nd7 25. Qa6 Qc7 26. Rc1
{ Black's c6 pawn is weak and White prepares to target it with c2-c4. } 26...
Re8 27. Qd3 Qd6 28. Qa6 Qc7 29. Rc2
{ is a useful move, covering the second rank. In positions where your opponent has no counterplay, you should NOT rush. You can afford to improve all your pieces to their maximum before going for a pawn break. }
29... f6
{ is unnecessary and only weakens Black's position. The a2-g8 diagonal is now more vulnerable.   29...Rd8  was better, passing the move onto White. }
30. Qd3 Nf8 31. c4 Qd7 32. c5 bxc5 33. dxc5
{ is the correct recapture, creating a fantastic outpost for the knight on d4. Creating a passed pawn with b5 is also in the cards. }
33... Qg4 34. Nd4 Ne6 35. Nxe6 Rxe6 36. Rb2 { Prepares to break with b5. }
36... Re1
{ is a decisive mistake that costs Black the game.   36...a6!  was necessary to keep White's pawns from rolling forward. After  37.b5  axb5  38.axb5  cxb5  39.Qxd5  Kh7=  Black should have little problems holding this endgame. }
37. b5 { Now there's no stopping White's b-pawn. } 37... Qxa4 38. b6 axb6 39.
cxb6 Re8 40. Re2 Rxe2
{ 40...Rb8  is strongly met by  41.Qxg6  when the b6 pawn is untouchable because of Re8+ and if  41...Qb4  42.h5  followed by h6 decides the game. Note how Black's 29...f6?! weakening move, allowing Qxg6, came back to haunt him! }
41. Qxe2 Qb4 42. h5
{ is very strong. White stretches Black's defense by combining threats against his king with the promotion of the b-pawn. }
42... gxh5
{ 42...Qxb6?  loses to  43.hxg6  Kf8  44.Qh5+-  followed by Qh8xg7 is decisive. }
43. Qe8+ Kh7 44. Qxh5+ Kg8 45. Qe8+ Kh7 46. Qxc6
{ The b-pawn will now queen. Black can give a bunch of checks but it won't change his fate. }
46... Qe4+ 47. Kf1 Qh1+ 48. Ke2 Qe4+ 49. Kd2 Qd4+ 50. Kc1 Qa1+ 51. Kc2 Qa2+ 52.
Kd3 Qb1+ 53. Kd4 Qb2+ 54. Kxd5
{ Black resigned as the checks will run out soon and the b-pawn will then decide the game.  1-0 @@StartBracket@@54@@EndBracket@@ Elyoseph,H @@StartBracket@@2379@@EndBracket@@-Bendana Aragon,J @@StartBracket@@2255@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2017 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Model games"]
[Black "1-0 (59) Anton Guijarro,D (2694) -Smeets,J (2585) Wijk aan Zee 2020"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a game in the mainline of the Petroff between Spanish phenomenon GM David Anton and Dutch GM Jan Smeets from the 2020 Tata Steel B tournament. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Be7 7. O-O Nc6 8.
Nbd2 Bf5 9. Re1 Nd6 10. Nf1 O-O 11. Bf4 Be6
{ is very passive.   11...Bxd3  is a better option. } 12. c3 Qd7 13. Qc2 g6 14.
Ne3
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, namely in the7...Be7 8...Bf5 #1 variation. }
14... Rfe8 15. h4
{ is the beginning of a big attack. Despite the symmetrical pawn structure, White can often start active operations on the kingside with h4-h5 and/or expand on the queenside with a4 and b4. Due to the weaknesses created by 13...g6, the former plan gains in strength here. }
15... Bf8 16. Ng5 Nd8 17. h5 Bg7 18. hxg6 hxg6 19. Re2
{ Prepares to double-up on the e-file. Black's pieces are stepping onto each other's toes and so he's in no position to counter White's control of this file. }
19... b6
{ vacates the b7 square to clear the back rank. The knight, however, will be completely misplaced on b7. }
20. Rae1 N8b7 21. Nxe6 Qxe6
{ putting the queen in danger is not a move Black wanted to make.   The alternative recapture  21...Rxe6  would have dropped the d5 pawn to  22.Nxd5+-   21...fxe6  is obviously terrible as it drops the g6 pawn to  22.Bxg6+- }
22. Nf5
{ Prepares to eliminate Black's dark-squared bishop, which is the main defender of his king. }
22... Qd7 23. Nxg7 Kxg7 24. Be5+ f6
{ is basically forced.   24...Kg8  runs into  25.Bxg6!  The bishop is untouchable as  25...fxg6??  results in a forced mate in 5:  26.Qxg6+  Kf8  27.Qh6+  Kg8  28.Qh8+  Kf7  29.Qg7+  Ke6  30.Qf6 }
25. Bxg6 fxe5 26. Bxe8
{ wins material but White has an even stronger option at his disposal.   26.dxe5!  was far stronger and would have decided the game in a matter of moves.  26...Ne4  27.Bxe4  dxe4  28.Qxe4+-  and Black's king is toast with Re3-g3 coming next. }
26... Rxe8 27. Rxe5
{ 27.dxe5  keeping both rooks on the board was stronger. Note that  27...Ne4  is strongly met by  28.c4+-  with a decisive advantage. }
27... Rxe5 28. dxe5 Ne4 29. f3 Ng5 30. Qd2
{ 30.f4!  activating White's pawn majority was stronger.  30...Ne6  31.f5  Ng5  32.Qd3+-  when there's no stopping White's pawns. }
30... Qf5 31. Qxd5 Nc5 32. Qd8 Nge6 33. Qf6+
{ transfers into an endgame White eventually won. However, he made converting the point much harder on himself. }
33... Qxf6 34. exf6+ Kxf6 35. Rd1 b5 36. g3 Na4 37. Rd2 a5 38. Kf2 Nb6 39. b3
a4 40. Ke2 Nc5 41. b4 Ne6 42. f4 a3 43. Kf3 Na4 44. Rc2 c6 45. g4
{ White's two connected passed pawns will now decide the game. } 45... Nc7 46.
Ke4 Nd5 47. g5+ Kg6 48. Ke5 Naxc3 49. Rc1
{ 49.f5+  would have won instantly, the point being that  49...Kxg5  50.Rg2+  Kh4  51.f6+-  forces Black to give up one of his knights. }
49... Kg7
{ 49...Nxa2  would have secured the draw with engine-like precision.  50.Rxc6+  Kh5  51.Ra6  Naxb4  52.Rxa3  Ne7  53.Rb3  Ng6+  54.Ke4  Nc6  55.Rxb5  Nce7  White has no way to make progress. Spotting all of this is however far from trivial and both players were already low on time at this point. }
50. f5 Nxa2 51. Ra1 Naxb4 52. Rxa3 Nc7 53. f6+ Kg6 54. Rf3 Nba6 55. f7 Nc5 56.
Rf6+ Kxg5 57. Rd6 N7e6 58. Rxe6 Nd7+ 59. Kd6
{ There is no stopping White's f-pawn so Black resigned.  1-0 @@StartBracket@@59@@EndBracket@@ Anton Guijarro,D @@StartBracket@@2694@@EndBracket@@ -Smeets,J @@StartBracket@@2585@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2020 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Model games"]
[Black "1-0 (43) Nepomniachtchi,I (2774)-Wang,H (2762) Candidates Ekaterinburg 2020"]
[Result "*"]

{ The following is a high-profile game between super-GMs Ian Nepomniachtchi and Wang Hao from the 2020 Candidates. It features the 6...Bf5 variation of the Petroff. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Bf5 7. O-O Be7 8.
Re1 O-O 9. Nbd2 Nd6 10. Nf1 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 c6 12. Bf4 Na6 13. h4 Nc7 14. Ng5
Bxg5 15. Bxg5 f6 16. Bf4 Qd7
{ This was all covered in the theoretical section of the course, namely in the12...Na6 14...Bxg5 variation in chapter 5. }
17. Ng3
{ White is ready to trade on d6 and then jump in with Nf5.   My recommendation in theory section was the novel  17.Ne3!  N which is more accurate than Nepo's choice.  17...Rae8  The key difference is that after   17...g6  18.h5  f5  19.hxg6  hxg6  White can now play  20.Ng4!  an option that is only possible with 17. Ne3.  18.Bxd6  Qxd6  19.Nf5  transposes to the game. }
17... Rae8
{ 17...g6  stopping Nf5 was worthy of consideration. This option would not have been available had Nepo played 17. Ne3 instead. }
18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. Nf5 Qd7 20. Qh3
{ Threatens to win material with Nh6+, which Wang Hao easily parried with }
20... Kh8 21. h5 Rxe1+
{ Trading off pieces to simplify the position is natural but not very accurate.   Better was  21...Nb5!  with the idea ...Nd6, which would have practically equalized. }
22. Rxe1 Re8 23. Rxe8+ Nxe8 24. g4
{ Reinforces the knight, thus freeing the queen which can now swing over to the queenside. The drawback is that White's king is now slightly more exposed.   The more restrained  24.Kf1  was also interesting. }
24... a6
{ Pre-empts Qa3.   Nepo set the small trap that  24...Nd6??  loses to  25.Qa3  the point being that  25...Nxf5  26.Qf8  is checkmate! }
25. b3
{ After a long think, Nepo decides to start active operations in the center. This is the only way of setting Black any problems.   25.Qe3  would have activated White's pieces to their maximum. The problem is that with only a knight and a queen, even if they're better placed, White has no way of making progress. }
25... Qe6 26. Ne3
{ White drops back the knight in anticipation of ...g6. From e3, the knight supports the c4 break and keeps the e-file closed.   The alternative  26.Qg3  gives White very little.  26...g6  27.Ne3  Kg7= }
26... Nd6
{ 26...b5  stopping c2-c4 was certainly worthy of consideration.   26...Qe4  looks active but it doesn't work because White can ignore the threat to the d-pawn and make threats of his own on the queenside. For example  27.Qg3  Qxd4  28.Qb8  Qe4  29.Qxb7  d4  30.Nf5  Qxg4+  31.Ng3  Qe6  32.Qxa6+-  is decisive. }
27. h6
{ 14 moves since 13. h4 was played, the h-pawn has finally arrived at its final destination. The h-pawn is a bone in Black's throat, who now has back rank problems. }
27... g6 28. c4 dxc4
{ Centralizing the king with  28...Kg8  was also sensible. } 29. bxc4 Kg8
{ 29...Nxc4  is not possible as after  30.Nxc4  Qxc4  the quiet retreating move  31.Qh2  is very strong. White threatens mate with Qb8 and keeps the h6 pawn protected @@StartBracket@@so it doesn't drop with ...Qc1+@@EndBracket@@.   29...Qe4!?  was very interesting. After  30.c5  Ne8  31.g5  f5  the position is very double-edged with all three results possible. }
30. Qh2 Kf7 31. c5 Nb5 32. Qb8
{ White has improved his position to the maximum possible. The queen has infiltrated the last rank. From b8, it's pressuring the b7 pawn and can also swing over to h8 to attack the h7 pawn. The knight on e3 also occupies its best post, keeping the g4 pawn and White's king protected. }
32... Qd7
{ is a mistake, which makes White's plan come together.   32...Qe7!  was far stronger and I suspect would have easily led to a draw. The difference is that after  33.Qh8  Ke6  Black's king now has the d7-square at his disposal. Black is still not out of the woods as White can continue playing with  34.Nc2!  intending Qg8+ next. Following  34...f5  35.Qg8+  Kd7=  White has no way of making progress.   32...Nxd4  was also possible. After  33.Qxb7+  Qe7  34.Qxa6  Qxc5  35.a4  The outside passer gives White some chances although Black is objectively fine with  35...f5=  creating counterplay on the kingside. }
33. Qh8 Ke6 34. f4 { Cages in Black's king. Next up is Qg8+. } 34... Nxd4 35.
Qg8+ Qf7 36. Qc8+ Qd7 37. Qg8+
{ Nepo repeats the position to get closer to move 40. } 37... Qf7 38. Qd8
{ White is threatening mate in one with Qd6# so Black has to play } 38... Qd7
{ but now } 39. f5+ { decides the game. } 39... gxf5 40. gxf5+ Nxf5 41. Qxd7+
Kxd7 42. Nxf5 { wins a knight, which is enough to decide the game. } 42... Ke6
43. Ne3
{ Wang Hao resigned.   The resignation was not premature as the extra knight easily decides the game. For example  43...Kf7  44.Nc4  Kg6  45.Nd6  Kxh6  46.Nxb7  Kh5  47.Nd8+−  will pick up the c6 pawn when White's c-pawn will then promote.  A nice, technical win by Nepomniachtchi who kept the tension high throughout several moves until Black eventually went wrong with the inaccurate 32...Qd7. His position quickly collapsed thereafter, but 32...Qe7 would have kept Black in the game.   1-0 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi,I @@StartBracket@@2774@@EndBracket@@-Wang,H @@StartBracket@@2762@@EndBracket@@ Ekaterinburg 2020 }
*

